# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dead-zone-ecology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The radio art of Schafer and his colleague, has found expression in many different fields.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] While most have taken some inspiration from Schafer's writings, in recent years there have also been divergences from the initial ideas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The expanded expressions of acoustic ecology are increasing due to the sonic impacts of road and airport construction that affect the soundscapes in and around cities where the human population is more dense.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] There has also been a broadening of bioacoustics (the use of sound by animals) to consider the subjective and objective responses of animals to human noise, with ocean noise capturing the most attention.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology can also be informative of changes in the climate or other environmental changes since every day we listen to sounds in the world to identify their source such as bird, car, plane, wind, water.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] But we don't listen those sounds as a network, a mesh of relationships that form an ecology.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology finds expression in many different fields that characterize a soundscape, which are biophony, geophony, and anthrophony.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Noise is generally a by-product of increased urbanization and development.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] As our cities became more industrialized, the volume and frequency of anthrophony, man-made noise signals, increased.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Noise can alter the acoustic environment of aquatic and terrestrial habitats.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Animal biodiversity has shown to decline because of chronic noise levels in cities and along roadways.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Musician and soundscape ecologist Bernie Krause relates biophony to an orchestra, where different groups of animals in an environment make sounds at different levels to avoid overlap or competition in their communication.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Manmade noise such as jets flying over a habitat can disrupt the natural order of these sounds, even putting certain species in danger of predators.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] For example, some frogs synchronize in a way that protects individuals from attracting attention.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The noise of a jet can cause the frogs to stop or fall out of sync, temporarily breaking this effect and exposing them to other animals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] On land, animal communication is shaped by physical characteristics of an environment such as distance, range of vision, weather, and surrounding noise.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The physical layout of a habitat may impede the spread of soundwaves while air conditions can affect sound quality and speed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Animals can adapt to factors like distance by adjusting the frequency and amplitute of their calls to maximize communication effectiveness.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Some species such as the urban great tits have changed the frequency of their calls to adapt.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes of particular habitats are always evolving because the activities and species that exist in those habitats changes over time.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] In terms of evolution, man-made noise is a much more recent phenomenon.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Indeed, through investigating collected recordings, ecologists can study ethology of animal acoustic communication, evolution, and development of acoustic behavior, relationships between animal sounds and their environment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] However, all those ecological research goals have a precondition that those bioacoustic recordings are well investigated so that the animal species can be accurately recognized.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Scientific research has shown that it has potential to change behavior, alter physiology and even restructure animal communities.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes are composed of the anthrophony, geophony and biophony of a particular environment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] They are specific to location and change over time.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology aims to study the relationship between these things, i.e. the relationship between humans, animals and nature, within these soundscapes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] These relationships are delicate and subject to disruption by natural or man-made means.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] In his book *The Tuning of the World*, Schafer used new terms like 'soundmarks' -- a specific community's distinctive sounds—and 'keynotes' -- prevalent but overlooked background sounds such as traffic—to help categorize the different elements of a soundscape.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Biophony is the study of sounds emerging from animal sources, like whale vocalizations or birdsong.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Geophony can be defined as the sounds originating from the Earth's natural processes, such as the blowing of wind or movement of waves.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Anthrophony is the soundscape defined by man-made sources, like speech or road noise.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Research on the relationship between visual and auditory experiences in urban settings finds that the positive or negative visual perceptions of a landscape can directly affect the emotional assessment of the location's soundscape.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] A pleasant view or comfortable surroundings can increase people's tolerance and even appreciation for the sounds of an environment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] People's preferences for noise control have been shown to differ based on the culture and technology of the time period as well as the familiarity or practicality of certain sounds.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] For example, accepted sources of loud noise such as church bells or trucks may not bother a neighborhood as much as someone's new leaf blower, even if it is not as loud as more familiar sounds.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] This is why it is considered difficult to generalize which sounds are unwanted in a community.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Studying the soundscapes and traumatic impact of war has shown the effectiveness of noise as a psychological weapon to produce fear.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Aircraft activity has been a continuing development around the world and has some very good potential to change social-ecological systems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] In Alaska, for example the communities are reporting that the aircraft disturb wildlife and negatively influence harvest practices and experiences.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The limited data has some restricted knowledge about the extent of aircraft activity over traditional harvest areas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] It is actually very impressive to see the amount of aircraft overflight around the rural subsistence, because the activity is increasing significantly and they have reached a median of 12 overflights per day near human development, which is six times greater than undeveloped areas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Therefore, those planes startle caribou prefer to avoid aircraft themselves, which has a result that they will need to go farther to do a better harvest, but this will occur in adding some costs for fuel, equipment, and the effort for sure.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Those kind of examples help to understand the impact on social-ecological dynamics in Antarctica.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The ambient noise present within the world's oceans; geophonic, anthrophonic, and biophonic, has been identified as a critical indicator to the well-being of the regional biosphere.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The acoustic niche hypothesis, as proposed by acoustic ecologist Bernie Krause in 1993, refers to the process in which organisms partition the acoustic domain, finding their own niche in frequency and/or time in order to communicate without competition from other species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The theory draws from the ideas of niche differentiation and can be used to predict differences between young and mature ecosystems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Similar to how interspecific competition can place limits on the number of coexisting species that can utilize a given availability of habitats or resources, the available acoustic space in an environment is a limited resource that is partitioned among those species competing to utilize it.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] In mature ecosystems, species will sing at unique bandwidths and specific times, displaying a lack of interspecies competition in the acoustic environment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Conversely, in young ecosystems, one is more likely to encounter multiple species using similar frequency bandwidths, which can result in interference between their respective calls, or a complete lack of activity in uncontested bandwidths.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Biological invasions can also result in interference in the acoustic niche, with non-native species altering the dynamics of the native community by producing signals that mask or degrade native signals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] This can cause a variety of ecological impacts, such as decreased reproduction, aggressive interactions, and altered predator-prey dynamics.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] The degree of partitioning in an environment can be used to indicate ecosystem health and biodiversity.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] "Dominion" uses Canadian soundmarks that were made in different province by the World Soundscape Project at Simon Fraser University for an event of cross-country tour that happened in 1973.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] What is interesting about those sounds is that they are stretched over the time, so the extended versions allowed the people that listen to the sound in a more harmonic way.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Those unique sound signals, were picked up by the live performers and then amplified to give the best experience possible to his audience.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] This is a subfield of archeology and acoustics that in general study the relation between people and sound along the history.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] This is an interdisciplinary field that has methodological contributions from acoustics, archeology and computer simulation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Many cultures explored through archaeology were mostly focused on the oral, which lead the researchers to believe that studying the sonic nature of archaeological sites and artifacts may reveal new information on the civilization being scrutinized.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] Moglen (2007) recreated pre-historical Soundscapes (Acoustic Ecology) at University of California, Berkeley's Department of Anthropology, combining compositional techniques with site recordings for a non-diegetic piece in the virtual world of Second Life, on "Okapi Island" .
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-ecology] At the Center for New Media the acoustic ecological setting of the former jazz scene in Oakland, CA was developed for a virtual world setting.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags transmit a signal made up of acoustic pulses or "pings" that send positional information of the tagged organism to a hydrophone receiver.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] By tying the received acoustic frequency to a predetermined and unique signal code, tagged animals can be identified at an individual level.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Transmitted signals may propagate up to 1 km (in freshwater) depending on tag model and environmental conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Receivers can be actively held by a researcher ("Active Tracking") or affixed to specific locations ("Passive Tracking").
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Arrays of receivers can allow the triangulation of tagged individuals over many kilometers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags are produced in many different shapes and sizes depending on the study organism or study environment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] The battery life of acoustic tags varies by size, with some larger tags lasting over four years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Sound parameters such as frequency and modulation method are chosen for optimal detectability and signal level.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] For oceanic environments, frequencies less than 100 kHz range are often used, while frequencies of several hundreds of kilohertz are more common in for studies in rivers and lakes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] A typical acoustic tag consists of a piezoceramic transducer, drive/timing electronics, and a battery power source.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Cylindrical or “tube” transducers are often used, which have metalization on the inner and outer walls of the structure.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] In normal operation, an alternating current (AC) electrical signal generated by the drive/timing electronics is impressed across the two metalization layers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] This voltage creates stress in the material, which in turn cause the transducer to emit an acoustic signal or “ping”, which emanates outward from the surface of the tube.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] An acoustic “ping” can be detected by specialized receivers, and processed using advanced signal processing techniques to determine if a fish swimming into the reception area carries a specific acoustic tag.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Several different methods are used to attach the tag to an organism.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] In fish, tags are frequently surgically implanted in the abdominal cavity.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Surgical implantation generally results in high tag retention, therefore it is regularly used.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Electro-immobilization with a TENS unit and chemical immobilization with compounds such as eugenol are commonly used to restrict fish movement during surgery.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] In some instances, tags are endogastrically implanted by forcing the tag down the gullet.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags may also be attached externally using additional braces or tag types.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] By determining the sound's time of arrival at each hydrophone, the 3D position of the fish can be calculated.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] The hydrophone receiver picks up the sound signal and converts it to data that researchers use to plot the resulting tag positions in three dimensions, in real-time.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Using a post processing software, such as *MarkTags*, takes that data and delivers the result, the 3D track.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] At present, acoustic tags are most commonly used to monitor fish approaching diversion and guidance structures at hydropower dams.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Ultimately, working to improve bypass effectiveness and protect fish populations, Acoustic Tag Tracking Systems are a significant breakthrough in the preservation of migrating salmon populations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags have been employed to help public utility agencies, private firms, and state and federal agencies meet fisheries regulations as defined by the Federal Regulations and Oversight of Energy (FERC Archived 2020-06-15 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] In the Laurentian Great Lakes, acoustic telemetry has addressed a variety of fishery research and management concerns through research conducted through the Great Lakes Acoustic Telemetry Observation System (GLATOS).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Estimates of spawning site fidelity have been made for lake trout and walleye.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Acoustic telemetry has also been used to inform invasive species management through the use of *Judas fish*, or tagged fish used to "betray" the location or behaviors of others.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags were used on sea lamprey in the Great Lakes to determine the effectiveness of traps at physical removal and to locate potential spawning locations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] They have also been used on common carp throughout North America to identify seasonal aggregations for future exploitation and removal.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Although incredibly valuable as a research and management tool, acoustic tags have some limitations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Foremost, the equipment required for acoustic telemetry (*e.g.*, tags, receivers, replacement batteries for receivers, mounting and deployment materials for receivers) can be cost-prohibitive especially in comparison to other techniques such as radio telemetry.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] For example, acoustic receivers can cost more than US$2,000 per unit while tags can range from $200 - US$1,000 per unit, depending on model.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Additionally, acoustic tags have variable detection range depending on habitat type, tag size, and environmental conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Variability in detection or poor detection probability could ultimately influence conclusions made from data and therefore is important to account for by range testing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/acoustic-tag] Considerations on project scale and timeframe are necessary before implementing acoustic telemetry.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The **Adriatic Sea** (/ˌeɪdriˈætɪk/) is a body of water separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic is the northernmost arm of the Mediterranean Sea, extending from the Strait of Otranto (where it connects to the Ionian Sea) to the northwest and the Po Valley.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The countries with coasts on the Adriatic are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Italy, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic contains more than 1,300 islands, mostly located along its eastern coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It is divided into three basins, the northern being the shallowest and the southern being the deepest, with a maximum depth of 1,233 metres (4,045 ft).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The prevailing currents flow counterclockwise from the Strait of Otranto.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Tidal movements in the Adriatic are slight, although larger amplitudes occur occasionally.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's salinity is lower than the Mediterranean's because it collects a third of the fresh water flowing into the Mediterranean, acting as a dilution basin.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The surface water temperatures generally range from 30 °C (86 °F) in summer to 12 °C (54 °F) in winter, significantly moderating the Adriatic Basin's climate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea sits on the Apulian or Adriatic Microplate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the Italian Peninsula first formed, separating the Adriatic Basin from the rest of the Mediterranean.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The western coast is alluvial or terraced, while the eastern coast is highly indented with pronounced karstification.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] There are dozens of marine protected areas in the Adriatic, designed to protect the sea's habitats and biodiversity—more than 7,000 species are identified as native to the Adriatic, many of them endemic, rare and threatened ones.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's shores are populated by more than 3.5 million people; the largest cities are Bari, Venice, Trieste and Split.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Early settlements on the Adriatic shores were Etruscan, Illyrian, and Greek.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] By the 2nd century BC, the region was under Rome's control.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Middle Ages, the sea was controlled, to a varying extent, by a series of states—most notably the Byzantine Empire, the Croatian Kingdom, the Republic of Venice, the Habsburg monarchy and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Napoleonic Wars resulted in the Austrian Empire gaining control of most of the eastern Adriatic shore and the Po Valley, while the Kingdom of Italy gradually took control of the remaining Italian coast during the 19th century.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Following the collapse of Austria-Hungary in 1918, control of the eastern coast passed to Yugoslavia and Albania, which agreed on their maritime boundaries with Italy in 1975 and 1992 respectively.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] After Yugoslavia's dissolution during the 1990s, its four coastal successor states—Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro—continued to recognise the previous maritime border with Italy, but have disputed the borders between themselves.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Fisheries and tourism are significant sources of income along the Adriatic coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Maritime transport is also a significant branch of the area's economy—there are 19 seaports in the Adriatic that each handle more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The largest Adriatic seaport by annual cargo turnover is the Port of Trieste, while the Port of Split is the largest by passengers served per year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The origins of the name *Adriatic* are linked to the Etruscan settlement of Adria, which probably derives its name from Illyrian *adur* 'water, sea'.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In classical antiquity, the sea was known as *Mare Adriaticum* (*Mare Hadriaticum*, also sometimes simplified to *Adria*) or, less frequently, as *Mare Superum* '[the] upper sea'.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The two terms were not synonymous, however.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] *Mare Adriaticum* generally corresponds to the Adriatic Sea's extent, spanning from the Gulf of Venice to the Strait of Otranto.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] That boundary became more consistently defined by Roman authors—early Greek sources place the boundary between the Adriatic and Ionian seas at various places ranging from adjacent to the Gulf of Venice to the southern tip of the Peloponnese, eastern shores of Sicily and western shores of Crete.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] *Mare Superum* on the other hand normally encompassed both the modern Adriatic Sea and the sea off the Apennine peninsula's southern coast, as far as the Strait of Sicily.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Another name used in the period was *Mare Dalmaticum*, applied to waters off the coast of Dalmatia or Illyricum.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] During the early modern period, the entire sea was also known as the **Gulf of Venice** (Italian: *golfo di Venezia*), although that name is now informally applied only to the northern area of the sea, from Maestra Point in the Po Delta to Cape Kamenjak on the Istrian Peninsula.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In Serbo-Croatian and Slovene, the sea is often referred to as simply *Jadran*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a semi-enclosed sea, bordered in the southwest by the Apennine or Italian Peninsula, in the northwest by the Italian regions of Veneto and Friuli-Venezia Giulia, and in the northeast by Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Albania—the Balkan peninsula.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the southeast, the Adriatic Sea connects to the Ionian Sea at the 72-kilometre (45 mi) wide Strait of Otranto.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It extends 800 kilometres (500 mi) from the northwest to the southeast and is 200 kilometres (120 mi) wide.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It covers 138,600 square kilometres (53,500 sq mi) and has a volume of 35,000 cubic kilometres (8,400 cu mi).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic extends northwest from 40° to 45°47' north, representing the Mediterranean's northernmost portion.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The sea is geographically divided into the Northern Adriatic, Central (or Middle) Adriatic, and Southern Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea drainage basin encompasses 235,000 square kilometres (91,000 sq mi), yielding a land–sea ratio of 1.8.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The drainage basin's mean elevation is 782 metres (2,566 ft) above sea level, with a mean slope of 12.1°.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Major rivers discharging into the Adriatic include the Po, Soča, Krka, Neretva, Drin, Buna, and Vjosë.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the late 19th century, Austria-Hungary established a geodetic network with an elevation benchmark using the average Adriatic Sea level at the Sartorio pier in Trieste, Italy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The benchmark was subsequently retained by Austria, adopted by Yugoslavia, and retained by the states that emerged after its dissolution.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In 2016, Slovenia adopted a new elevation benchmark referring to the upgraded tide gauge station in the coastal town of Koper.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Alps, which also have a large meteorological impact on the Mediterranean, touch the Adriatic in the area around Trieste towards Duino and Barcola.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea contains more than 1,300 islands and islets, most along the Adriatic's eastern coast—especially in Croatia, with 1,246 counted.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The number includes islands, islets, and rocks of all sizes, including ones emerging at ebb tide only.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Croatian islands include the largest—Cres and Krk, each covering about the same area of 405.78 square kilometres (156.67 sq mi)—and the tallest—Brač, whose peak reaches 780 metres (2,560 ft) above sea level.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The islands of Cres and the adjacent Lošinj are separated only by a narrow navigable canal dug in the time of classical antiquity; the original single island was known to the Greeks as Apsyrtides.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Croatian islands include 47 permanently inhabited ones, the most populous among them being Krk, Korčula and Brač.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The islands along the Adriatic's western (Italian) coast are smaller and less numerous than those along the opposite coast; the best-known ones are the 117 islands on which the city of Venice is built.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The northern shore of the Greek island of Corfu also lies in the Adriatic Sea as defined by the IHO.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The IHO boundary places the Diapontia Islands (northwest of Corfu) in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea's average depth is 259.5 metres (851 ft), and its maximum depth is 1,233 metres (4,045 ft); however, the North Adriatic basin rarely exceeds a depth of 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The North Adriatic basin, extending between Venice and Trieste towards a line connecting Ancona and Zadar, is only 15 metres (49 ft) deep at its northwestern end; it gradually deepens towards the southeast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It is the largest Mediterranean shelf and is simultaneously a dilution basin and a site of bottom water formation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Middle Adriatic basin is south of the Ancona–Zadar line, with the 270-metre (890 ft) deep Middle Adriatic Pit (also called the Pomo Depression or the Jabuka Pit).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The 170-metre (560 ft) deep Palagruža Sill is south of the Middle Adriatic Pit, separating it from the 1,200-metre (3,900 ft) deep South Adriatic Pit and the Middle Adriatic basin from the South Adriatic Basin.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Further on to the south, the sea floor rises to 780 metres (2,560 ft) to form the Otranto Sill at the boundary to the Ionian Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The South Adriatic Basin is similar in many respects to the Northern Ionian Sea, to which it is connected.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The coast's ruggedness is exacerbated by the Dinaric Alps' proximity to the coast, in contrast to the opposite (Italian) coast where the Apennine Mountains are further away from the shoreline.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The coastal water dynamics are determined by the asymmetric coasts and the inflow of the Mediterranean seawater through the Straits of Otranto and further on along the eastern coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The smooth Italian coast (with very few protrusions and no major islands) allows the Western Adriatic Current, which is composed of the relatively freshwater mass on the surface and the cold and dense water mass at the bottom, to flow smoothly.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The coastal currents on the opposite shore are far more complex owing to the jagged shoreline, several large islands and the proximity of the Dinaric Alps to the shore.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The last produces significant temperature variations between the sea and the hinterland, which leads to the creation of local jets.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The tidal movement is normally slight, usually remaining below 30 centimetres (12 in).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The amphidromic point is at the mid-width east of Ancona.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The normal tide levels are known to increase significantly in a conducive environment, leading to coastal flooding; this phenomenon is most famously known in Italy—especially Venice—as *acqua alta*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Such tides can exceed normal levels by more than 140 centimetres (55 in), with the highest tide level of 194 centimetres (76 in) observed on 4 November 1966.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Such flooding is caused by a combination of factors, including the alignment of the Sun and Moon, meteorological factors such as sirocco related storm surges, and the basin's geometric shape (which amplifies or reduces the astronomical component).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Moreover, the Adriatic's long and narrow rectangular shape is the source of an oscillating water motion (French: *seiche*) along the basin's minor axis.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Finally, Venice is increasingly vulnerable to flooding due to coastal area soil subsidence.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Such unusually high tides resulting in flooding have also been observed elsewhere in the Adriatic Sea, and have been recorded in recent years in the towns of Koper, Zadar and Šibenik as well.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It is estimated that the Adriatic's entire volume is exchanged through the Strait of Otranto in 3.4±0.4 years, a comparatively short period.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] (For instance, approximately 500 years are necessary to exchange all the Black Sea's water.) This short period is particularly important as the rivers flowing into the Adriatic discharge up to 5,700 cubic metres per second (200,000 cu ft/s).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] This rate of discharge amounts to 0.5% of the total Adriatic Sea volume, or a 1.3-metre (4 ft 3 in) layer of water each year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The greatest portion of the discharge from any single river comes from the Po (28%), with an average discharge from it alone of 1,569 cubic metres per second (55,400 cu ft/s).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In terms of the annual total discharge into the entire Mediterranean Sea, the Po is ranked second, followed by the Neretva and Drin, which rank as third and fourth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Another significant contributor of freshwater to the Adriatic is the submarine groundwater discharge through submarine springs (Croatian: *vrulja*); it is estimated to comprise 29% of the total water flux into the Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The submarine springs include thermal springs, discovered offshore near the town of Izola.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The thermal spring water is rich with hydrogen sulfide, has a temperature of 22 to 29.6 °C (71.6 to 85.3 °F), and has enabled the development of specific ecosystems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The inflow of freshwater, representing a third of the freshwater volume flowing into the Mediterranean, makes the Adriatic a dilution basin for the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Middle and South Adriatic Gyres (SAG), are significant cyclonic circulation features, with the former being intermittent and the latter permanent.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The SAG measures 150 kilometres (93 miles) in diameter.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It contributes to the flow of bottom water from the Adriatic to the Levantine Basin through the Ionian Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Through that process, the Adriatic Sea produces most of the East Mediterranean deep water.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's surface temperature usually ranges from 22 to 30 °C (72 to 86 °F) in the summer, or 12 to 14 °C (54 to 57 °F) in the winter, except along the western Adriatic coast's northern part, where it drops to 9 °C (48 °F) in the winter.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The distinct seasonal temperature variations, with a longitudinal gradient in the Northern and transversal gradient in the Middle and Southern Adriatic, are attributed to the continental characteristics of the Adriatic Sea: it is shallower and closer to land than are oceans.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] During particularly cold winters, sea ice may appear in the Adriatic's shallow coastal areas, especially in the Venetian Lagoon but also in isolated shallows as far south as Tisno (south of Zadar).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Southern Adriatic is about 8 to 10 °C (14 to 18 °F) warmer during the winter than the more northerly regions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's salinity variation over the year is likewise distinct: it ranges between 38 and 39 PSUs, somewhat higher than the range of 32 to 37 PSUs for the open ocean.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The southern Adriatic is subjected to saltier water from the Levantine Basin.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, the upper half of the Adriatic is classified as humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with wetter summers and colder and drier winters, and the southern Adriatic are classified as hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The air temperature can fluctuate by about 20 °C (36 °F) during a season.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The predominant winter winds are the bora and sirocco (called *jugo* along the eastern coast).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The bora is significantly conditioned by wind gaps in the Dinaric Alps bringing cold and dry continental air; it reaches peak speeds in the areas of Trieste, Senj, and Split, with gusts of up to 180 kilometres per hour (97 kn; 110 mph).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The sirocco brings humid and warm air, often carrying Saharan sand causing rain dust.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] On the Adriatic Sea's coasts and islands, there are numerous small settlements and a number of larger cities.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Among the largest are (counterclockwise) Trieste, Venice, Rimini, Ancona, Pescara and Bari in Italy; Vlorë and Durrës in Albania; Split, Zadar and Rijeka in Croatia; Koper in Slovenia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In total, more than 3.5 million people live on the Adriatic coasts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] There are also some larger cities that are located very near the coast, such as the Italian cities of Ravenna and Lecce.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Venice, which was originally built on islands off the coast, is most at risk due to subsidence, but the threat is present in the Po delta as well.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The causes are a decrease in sedimentation rate due to loss of sediment behind dams, the deliberate excavation of sand for industrial purposes, agricultural use of water, and removal of ground water.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The sinking of Venice slowed after artesian wells were banned in the 1960s, but the city remains threatened by the *acqua alta* floods.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Recent studies have suggested that the city is no longer sinking, but a state of alert remains in place.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In May 2003, then-Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi inaugurated the MOSE project (Italian: *Modulo Sperimentale Elettromeccanico*), an experimental model for evaluating the performance of inflatable gates.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The project proposes laying a series of 79 inflatable pontoons across the sea bed at the three entrances to the Venetian Lagoon.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] When tides are predicted to rise above 110 centimetres (43 in), the pontoons will be filled with air and block the incoming water from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] This engineering work was due to be completed by 2014, but as of November 2020 is expected to be completed in 2021.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] However, concern has been raised regarding the frequency of its use—while only necessary a few days a year, the worst-case sea level rise scenario between 2050 and 2100 would prompt deployment up to 187 days a year, essentially cutting off the Venetian Lagoon from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Among other possible adverse effects, this can be expected to lower the lagoon's oxygen levels and trap pollution inside of the city.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Geophysical and geological information indicate that the Adriatic Sea and the Po Valley are associated with a tectonic microplate—identified as the Apulian or Adriatic Plate—that separated from the African Plate during the Mesozoic era.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] This separation began in the Middle and Late Triassic, when limestone began to be deposited in the area.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Between the Norian and Late Cretaceous, the Adriatic and Apulia Carbonate Platforms formed as a thick series of carbonate sediments (dolomites and limestones), up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) deep.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Remnants of the former are found in the Adriatic Sea, as well as in the southern Alps and the Dinaric Alps, and remnants of the latter are seen as the Gargano Promontory and the Maiella mountain.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Eocene and early Oligocene, the plate moved north and north-east, contributing to the Alpine orogeny (along with the African and Eurasian Plates' movements) via the tectonic uplift of the Dinarides and Alps.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the motion was reversed and the Apennine Mountains' orogeny took place.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] An unbroken zone of increased seismic activity borders the Adriatic Sea, with a belt of thrust faults generally oriented in the northeast–southwest direction on the east coast and the northeast–southwest normal faults in the Apennines, indicating an Adriatic counterclockwise rotation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] An active 200-kilometre (120 mi) fault has been identified to the northwest of Dubrovnik, adding to the Dalmatian islands as the Eurasian Plate slides over the Adriatic microplate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Furthermore, the fault causes the Apennine peninsula's southern tip to move towards the opposite shore by about 0.4 centimetres (0.16 in) per year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] If this movement continues, the seafloor will be completely consumed and the Adriatic Sea closed off in 50–70 million years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Northern Adriatic, the coast of the Gulf of Trieste and western Istria is gradually subsiding, having sunk about 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in) in the past two thousand years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Middle Adriatic Basin, there is evidence of Permian volcanism in the area of Komiža on the island of Vis and the volcanic islands of Jabuka and Brusnik.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Earthquakes have been observed in the region since the earliest historical records.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] A recent strong earthquake in the region was the 1979 Montenegro earthquake, measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Historical earthquakes in the area include the 1627 Gargano peninsula and the 1667 Dubrovnik earthquakes, both followed by strong tsunamis.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the last 600 years, fifteen tsunamis have occurred in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] All types of seafloor sediments are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Northern Adriatic's comparatively shallow seabed is characterised by relict sand (from times when the water level was lower and the area was a sandy beach), while a muddy bed is typical at depths below 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Sediments deposited in the Adriatic Sea today generally come from the northwest coast, being carried by the Po, Reno, Adige, Brenta, Tagliamento, Piave and Soča rivers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The volume of sediments carried from the eastern shore by the Rječina, Zrmanja, Krka, Cetina, Ombla, Dragonja, Mirna, Raša and Neretva rivers is negligible, because these sediments are mostly deposited at the river mouths.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's western shores are largely either alluvial or terraced, whereas the eastern shores are predominantly rocky, except for the southernmost part of the shore located in Albania that consists of sandy coves and rocky capes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The eastern Adriatic shore's Croatian part is the most indented Mediterranean coastline.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Most of the eastern coast is characterised by a karst topography, developed from the Adriatic Carbonate Platform's exposure to weathering.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Karstification there largely began after the Dinarides' final uplift in the Oligocene and the Miocene, when carbonate deposits were exposed to atmospheric effects; this extended to the level of 120 metres (390 ft) below the present sea level, exposed during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It is estimated that some karst formations are from earlier sea level drops, most notably the Messinian salinity crisis.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Similarly, karst developed in Apulia from the Apulian Carbonate Platform.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Rocks of the same type are found in Albania and on the western Adriatic coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] There are alternations of maritime and alluvial sediments occurring in the Po Valley, at the Adriatic's north-west coast, and as far west as Piacenza, dating to the Pleistocene as the sea advanced and receded over the valley.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] An advance began after the Last Glacial Maximum, which brought the Adriatic to a high point at about 5,500 years ago.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Since then, the Po delta has been prograding (expanding/extending).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The rate of coastal zone progradation between 1000 BC and 1200 AD was 4 metres (13 ft) per year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the 12th century, the delta advanced at a rate of 25 metres (82 ft) per year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the 17th century, the delta began to become a human-controlled environment, as the excavation of artificial channels started; the channels and new distributaries of the Po have been prograding at rates of 50 metres (160 ft) per year or more since then.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] There are more than 20 other rivers flowing into the Adriatic Sea in Italy alone, also forming alluvial coastlines, including the lagoons of Venice, Grado and Caorle.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] There are smaller eastern Adriatic alluvial coasts—in the deltas of the Dragonja, Buna and Neretva rivers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a unique water body in respect of its overall biogeochemical physiognomy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It exports inorganic nutrients and imports particulate organic carbon and nitrogen through the Strait of Otranto—acting as a mineralization site.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The exchange of the substances is made more complex by bathymetry of the Adriatic Sea—75% of water flowing north through the strait recirculates at the Palagruža Sill and North Adriatic adds no more than 3–4% of water to the South Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] This is reflected in its biogeography and ecology, and particularly in the composition and properties of its ecosystems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Its main biogeographic units are the Northern Adriatic, the Central Adriatic, and the Southern Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The unique nature of the Adriatic gives rise to an abundance of endemic flora and fauna.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Croatian National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan identified more than 7,000 animal and plant species in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Central Adriatic is especially abundant in endemic plant species, with 535 identified species of green, brown and red algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Four out of five Mediterranean seagrass species are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The most common species are *Cymodocea nodosa* and *Zostera noltii*, while *Zostera marina* and *Posidonia oceanica* are comparatively rare.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] This circulation has significantly contributed to the biodiversity of the countries along the eastern Adriatic coast; the common bottlenose dolphin is frequent in the eastern coast's waters only, and the Croatian coast provides refuge for the critically endangered monk seal and sea turtles.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Recent studies revealed that cetaceans and other marine megafaunas, that were once thought to be vagrants to Adriatic Sea, migrate and live in the semi-closed sea on larger scales.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Largest of these live normally is the fin whale, and sperm whale, the largest of toothed whales also migrate but less common than fin whales, followed by Cuvier's beaked whales.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Basking sharks and manta rays are some of migrant species to the sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Historical presences of depleted or extinct species such as North Atlantic right whales (extinct or functionally extinct), Atlantic gray whales (extinct), and humpback whales have been speculated as well.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Tuna has been caught by the locals in the upper Adriatic for thousands of years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The very large schools consisted mainly of little tunny and moved as far as the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] However, increasing fishing prevented the migration of large schools of fish to the north.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The last major tuna catch was made there in 1954 by the fishermen from Santa Croce, Contovello and Barcola.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Northern Adriatic in particular is rich in endemic fish fauna.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Around thirty species of fish are found in only one or two countries bordering the Adriatic Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] These are particularly due to or dependent upon the karst morphology of the coastal or submarine topography; this includes inhabiting subterranean habitats, karst rivers, and areas around freshwater springs.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] There are 45 known subspecies endemic to the Adriatic's coasts and islands.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In the Adriatic, there are at least 410 species and subspecies of fish, representing approximately 70% of Mediterranean taxa, with at least 7 species endemic to the Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Sixty-four known species are threatened with extinction, largely because of overfishing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Only a small fraction of the fish found in the Adriatic are attributed to recent processes such as Lessepsian migration, and escape from mariculture.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The biodiversity of the Adriatic is relatively high, and several marine protected areas have been established by countries along its coasts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In Italy, these are Miramare in the Gulf of Trieste (in the Northern Adriatic), Torre del Cerrano and Tremiti Islands in the Middle Adriatic basin and Torre Guaceto in southern Apulia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Miramare protected area was established in 1986 and covers 30 hectares (74 acres) of coast and 90 hectares (220 acres) of sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The area encompasses 1.8 kilometres (1.1 mi) of coastline near the Miramare promontory in the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Torre del Cerrano protected area was created in 2009, extending 3 nautical miles (5.6 km; 3.5 mi) into the sea and along 7 kilometres (4.3 mi) of coastline.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Various zones of the protected area cover 37 square kilometres (14 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Tremiti Islands reserve has been protected since 1989, while the Tremiti islands themselves are part of the Gargano National Park.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Torre Guaceto protected area, located near Brindisi and Carovigno, covers a sea surface of 2,227 hectares (5,500 acres) and is adjacent to the Torre Guaceto State Reserve covering 1,114 hectares (2,750 acres) of coast and sharing an 8-kilometre (5.0 mi) coastline with the marine protected area.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Furthermore, there are 10 internationally important (Ramsar) wetland reserves in Italy located along the Adriatic coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Brijuni national park encompasses the 743.3-hectare (1,837-acre) archipelago itself and 2,651.7 hectares (6,552 acres) of surrounding sea; it became a national park in 1999.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Lim Canal is a 10-kilometre (6.2 mi) ria of the Pazinčica river.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Kornati national park was established in 1980; it covers approximately 220 square kilometres (85 sq mi), including 89 islands and islets.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The marine environment encompasses three-quarters of the total area, while the island shores' combined length equals 238 kilometres (148 mi).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Telašćica is a nature park established on Dugi Otok in 1988.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The park covers 69 kilometres (43 mi) of coastline, 22.95 square kilometres (8.86 sq mi) of land and 44.55 square kilometres (17.20 sq mi) of sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Bay of Mali Ston is located at the border of Croatia and Bosnia–Herzegovina, north of the Pelješac peninsula.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The marine protected area covers 48 square kilometres (19 sq mi).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Lastovo nature park was established in 2006, and it includes 44 islands and islets, 53 square kilometres (20 sq mi) of land and 143 square kilometres (55 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Mljet national park was established in 1960, covering a 24-square-kilometre (9.3 sq mi) marine protection area.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In addition, there is a Ramsar wetland reserve in Croatia—the Neretva river's delta.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In Slovenia, the marine and coastal protected nature areas are the Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park, Strunjan Landscape Park, Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve, and the Debeli Rtič, Cape Madona and Lakes in Fiesa natural monuments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park was established in 1990, covers 721 hectares (1,780 acres), and includes four nature reserves.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In 1993, the area was designated a Ramsar site; it is also a site of international importance for waterbird species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The 429-hectare (1,060-acre) Strunjan Landscape Park was established in 2004 and comprises two nature reserves.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It includes a 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) long cliff, the northernmost Mediterranean salt field and the only Slovenian lagoon system.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It is also the northernmost point of growth of some Mediterranean plant species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve was established in 1998 and covers 122 hectares (300 acres).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Debeli Rtič natural monument covers 24 hectares (59 acres), the Cape Madona natural monument covers 12 hectares (30 acres), and the Lakes in Fiesa natural monument, with the coastal lake as the only brackish lake in Slovenia, covers 2.1 hectares (5.2 acres).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In 2010, Albania established its first marine protection area, the Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park at the Karaburun Peninsula where the Adriatic and Ionian Seas meet.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The park covers a total of 12,570 hectares (31,100 acres).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Two additional marine protection areas are planned in Albania: the Cape of Rodon (Albanian: *Kepi i Rodonit*) and Porto Palermo.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] In addition, Albania is home to two Ramsar wetland reserves: Karavasta Lagoon, and Butrint.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Neither Bosnia–Herzegovina nor Montenegro have or plan to establish any marine protection areas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea ecosystem is threatened by excessive input of nutrients through drainage from agricultural land and wastewater flowing from cities; this includes both along its coast and from rivers draining into the sea—especially from the Po River.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Venice is often cited as an example of polluted coastal waters where shipping, transportation, farming, manufacturing and wastewater disposal contribute to polluting the sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] A further risk is presented by ballast water discharge by ships, especially tankers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Still, since most of the cargo handled by the Adriatic ports, and virtually all liquid (tanker) cargo handled by the ports, is coming to—not coming from—the Adriatic Basin, the risk from ballast water (from tankers expelling ballast water then loading in the Adriatic) remains minimal.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] However, proposed export oil pipelines were objected to specifically because of this issue.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Oil spills are a major concern in terms of potential environmental impact and damage to tourism and fisheries.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] It is estimated that if a major oil spill happened, a million people would lose their livelihoods in Croatia alone.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] An additional risk is presented by oil refineries in the Po River basin where oil spills have occurred before, in addition to accidents occurring in the Adriatic already, so far with no significant environmental consequences.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Since 2006, Italy has been considering the construction of an offshore and an onshore LNG terminal in the Gulf of Trieste, as well as a pipeline, in the immediate vicinity of the Slovenian–Italian border.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] The Slovenian government and municipalities, the municipal council of Trieste, and non-governmental organisations have voiced concern over their environmental hazards, effect on transport and effect on tourism.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Another source of pollution of the Adriatic is solid waste.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Drifting waste—occasionally relatively large quantities of material, especially waste plastic—is transported northwest by the sirocco.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Air pollution in the Adriatic Basin is associated with the large industrial centres in the Po River valley and the large industrial cities along the coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Italy and Yugoslavia established a joint commission to protect the Adriatic Sea from pollution in 1977; the organization later changed with Slovenia, Croatia and Montenegro replacing Yugoslavia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] Future pollution hazards are addressed and pollution hotspots are assessed not only by nations in the basin but also through regional projects with World Bank support.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p01] 27 such hotspots have been determined as of 2011, 6 warranting an urgent response.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Settlements along the Adriatic dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC appear in Albania and Dalmatia on the eastern Adriatic coast, related to the Cardium pottery culture.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During classical antiquity, Illyrians inhabited the eastern coast, and the western coast was inhabited by the peoples of Ancient Italy, mainly Etruscans, before the Roman Republic's rise.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Greek colonisation of the Adriatic dates back to the 7th and 6th centuries BC when the ancient cities of Epidamnos and Apollonia were founded.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Greeks soon expanded further north establishing several cities, including Ancona, Black Corcyra, Epidaurus, Issa, with trade established as far north as the Po River delta, where an emporium (trading station) was founded in Adria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Roman economic and military influence in the region began to grow with the creation by 246 BC of a major naval base at Brundisium (now Brindisi), which was established to bar Carthaginian ships from the Adriatic during the Punic Wars.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] This led to conflict with the Illyrians, who lived in a collection of semi-Hellenized kingdoms that covered much of the Balkans and controlled the eastern shore of the sea, resulting in the Illyrian Wars from 229 to 168 BC.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The initial Roman intervention in 229 BC, motivated in part by a desire to suppress Illyrian piracy in the Adriatic, marked the first time that the Roman navy crossed that sea to launch a military campaign.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Those wars ended with the eastern shore becoming a province of the Roman Republic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] However, resistance to Roman rule continued sporadically and Rome did not completely consolidate control of the region until Augustus's general Tiberius put down the Great Illyrian Revolt, a bitter struggle waged from 6 to 9 AD.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Following the repression of the revolt the Roman province of Illyricum was split into Dalmatia and Pannonia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During the Roman period, Brundisium, on the western shore, and Apollonia and Dyrrachium (originally called Epidamnos, now Durrës in Albania) on the eastern shore became important ports.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Brundisium was linked by the Via Appia road to the city of Rome, and Dyrrachium and Apollonia were both on the Via Egnatia, a road that by about 130 BC the Romans had extended eastward across the Balkans to Byzantium (later Constantinople, now Istanbul).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] This made the sea passage across the Adriatic between Brundisium and Dyrrachium (or Apollonia) a link in the primary route for travelers, trade, and troop movements, between Rome and the East.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] This route played a major role in some of the military operations that marked the end of the Roman Republic and the start of the imperial period.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Sulla used it during the First Mithridatic War.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Marc Antony and Octavian (later Augustus) crossed the Adriatic to Dyrrachium with their armies in their campaign against two of Caesar's assassins, Brutus and Cassius, that culminated in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Brundisium and Dyrrachium remained important ports well after the Roman period, but an earthquake in the 3rd century AD changed the path of a river causing Apollonia's harbor to silt up, and the city to decline.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Another city on the Italian coast of the Adriatic that increased in importance during the Roman era was Ravenna.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During the reign of Augustus, it became a major naval base as part of his program to re-organize the Roman navy to better protect commerce in the Mediterranean.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During the 4th century AD the emperors of the Western Roman Empire had moved their official residence north from Rome to Mediolanum (now Milan) in order to be better able to control the military frontier with the Germanic tribes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 402 AD, during a period of repeated Germanic invasions of Italy, the capital was shifted to Ravenna because nearby marshes made it more defensible, and the Adriatic provided an easy escape path by sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] When the Western Empire fell in 476 AD Ravenna became the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the Early Middle Ages, after the Roman Empire's decline, the Adriatic's coasts were ruled by Ostrogoths, Lombards and the Byzantine Empire.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Ostrogothic Kingdom ruled Italy following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 AD.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] However, during the reign of Justinian the Byzantine Empire sent an army under the general Belisarius to regain control of Italy, resulting in the Gothic War (535–554).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Byzantines established the Exarchate of Ravenna and by 553 AD their viceroy (Exarch) ruled almost the entire Italian peninsula from that city.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 568 AD the Lombards invaded northern Italy, and over the course of the next century or so the importance of the Exarchate declined as the territory under Lombard control expanded and as the Byzantine outpost of Venice became increasingly independent.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 752 AD the Lombards overthrew the Exarchate, ending the influence of the Byzantine Empire on the western shore of the Adriatic for a few centuries.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Republic of Venice, one of the maritime republics, was founded during this period and went on to become a significant maritime power after receiving a Byzantine tax exemption in 1082.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The end of the period brought about the Holy Roman Empire's control over the Kingdom of Italy (which would last until the Peace of Westphalia in 1648), the establishment of an independent Kingdom of Croatia and the Byzantine Empire's return to the southern Apennine peninsula.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In addition, the Papal States were carved out in the area around Rome and central Italy in the 8th century.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In this period, the Republic of Venice began to expand its territory and influence.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 1202, the Fourth Crusade was diverted to conquer Zadar at the behest of the Venetians—the first instance of a Crusader force attacking a Catholic city—before proceeding to sack Constantinople.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the 13th century, Venice established itself as a leading maritime nation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During much of the 12th and 13th centuries, Venice and the Republic of Genoa were engaged in warfare culminating in the War of Chioggia, ousting the Genoese from the Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Still, the 1381 Treaty of Turin that ended the war required Venice to renounce claims to Dalmatia, after losing the territory to Hungary in 1358.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the same year, the Republic of Ragusa was established in Dubrovnik as a city-state after it was freed from Venetian suzerainty.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Venice regained Dalmatia in 1409 and held it for nearly four hundred years, with the republic's apex of trading and military power in the first half of the 15th century.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] These defeats spelled the end of an independent Hungarian kingdom, and both Croatian and Hungarian nobility chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as their new ruler, bringing the Habsburg monarchy to the shore of the Adriatic Sea, where it would remain for nearly four hundred years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Ottomans and Venetians fought a series of wars, but until the 17th century these were not fought in the Adriatic area.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Ottoman raids on the Adriatic coasts effectively ceased after the massive setback in the Battle of Lepanto in October 1571.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The 17th century's final territorial changes were caused by the Morean or Sixth Ottoman–Venetian War, when in 1699 Venice slightly enlarged its possessions in Dalmatia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 1797, the Republic of Venice was abolished after the French conquest.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Venetian territory was then handed over to Austria and briefly ruled as part of the Archduchy of Austria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The territory was turned back over to France after the Peace of Pressburg in 1805 when the territory in the Po valley became an integral part of the new Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The new kingdom included the province of Romagna, thus removing the Papal State from the Adriatic coast; however, Trieste, Istria and Dalmatia were joined into a set of separate provinces of the French Empire: the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] These were created in 1809 through the Treaty of Schönbrunn; they represented the end of Venetian rule on the eastern Adriatic coast, as well as the end of the Republic of Ragusa.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic Sea was a minor theatre in the Napoleonic Wars; the Adriatic campaign of 1807–1814 involved the Royal Navy contesting the Adriatic's control by the combined navies of France, Italy and the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During the campaign, the British navy occupied Vis and established its base there in Port St.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The campaign reached its climax in the 1811 Battle of Lissa, and ended with British and Austrian forces seizing the coastal cities on the eastern Adriatic coast from the French.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Days before the Battle of Waterloo, the Congress of Vienna awarded the Illyrian Provinces (spanning from the Gulf of Trieste to the Bay of Kotor) to Austria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Congress of Vienna also created the Kingdom of Lombardy–Venetia which encompassed the city of Venice, the surrounding coast and a substantial hinterland, and was controlled by Austria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the Apennine peninsula's south, the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was formed in 1816 by unifying the kingdoms of Naples and Sicily.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The process of Italian unification culminated in the Second Italian War of Independence, resulting in the Kingdom of Sardinia annexing all territories along the western Adriatic coast south of Venetia in 1860, and the 1861 establishment of the Kingdom of Italy in its place.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Kingdom of Italy expanded in 1866: it annexed Venetia, but its navy was defeated in the Adriatic near Vis.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Following the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 and the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868, the control of much of the eastern Adriatic coast was redefined.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The cisleithanian (Austrian) part of Austria-Hungary spanned from the Austrian Littoral to the Bay of Kotor, with the exception of the Croatian Littoral mainland.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the territory outside the Austrian Littoral, special status was given to Fiume (modern-day Rijeka) as a separate part of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The rest of the territory was made a part of the Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia, which in turn was also in the Transleithanian part of the dual monarchy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic coastline controlled by the Ottoman Empire was reduced by the Congress of Berlin in 1878, through recognition of the independence of the Principality of Montenegro, which controlled the coast south of the Bay of Kotor to the Bojana River.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Ottoman Empire lost all territories along the Adriatic following the First Balkan War and consequent 1913 Treaty of London that established an independent Albania.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The World War I Adriatic Campaign was largely limited to blockade attempts by the Allies and the effort of the Central Powers to thwart the British, French and Italian moves.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Italy joined the Allies in April 1915 with the Treaty of London, which promised Italy the Austrian Littoral, northern Dalmatia, the port of Vlorë, most of the eastern Adriatic islands and Albania as a protectorate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The treaty provided the basis for all the following divisions between Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 1918, the Montenegrin national assembly voted to unite with the Kingdom of Serbia, giving the latter access to the Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Another short-lived, unrecognised state established in 1918 was the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs, formed from parts of Austria-Hungary, comprising most of the former monarchy's Adriatic coastline.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Later that year, the Kingdom of Serbia and the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs formed the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes—subsequently renamed Yugoslavia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The proponents of the new union in the Croatian parliament saw the move as a safeguard against Italian expansionism as stipulated in the Treaty of London.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The treaty was largely disregarded by Britain and France because of conflicting promises made to Serbia and a perceived lack of Italian contribution to the war effort outside Italy itself.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The 1919 Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye did transfer the Austrian Littoral and Istria to Italy but awarded Dalmatia to Yugoslavia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Following the war, a private force of demobilized Italian soldiers seized Rijeka and set up the Italian Regency of Carnaro—seen as a harbinger of Fascism—in order to force the recognition of Italian claims to the city.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During World War II, the Adriatic saw only limited naval action, starting with the Italian invasion of Albania and the joint Axis invasion of Yugoslavia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The latter led to the annexation of a large part of Dalmatia and nearly all the eastern Adriatic islands by Italy and the establishment of two puppet states, the Independent State of Croatia and the Kingdom of Montenegro, which controlled the remainder of the former Yugoslav Adriatic coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 1947, after the Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces and the war's end, Italy (now a republic) and the Allies signed the Treaty of Peace with Italy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The FTT was partitioned in 1954: Trieste itself and the area to the North of it were placed under Italian control, while the rest came under Yugoslav control.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] This arrangement was made permanent in the 1975 Treaty of Osimo.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] During the Cold War, the Adriatic Sea became the southernmost flank of the Iron Curtain as Italy joined NATO, while the Warsaw Pact established bases in Albania.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] After the fall of communism, Yugoslavia broke apart: Slovenia and Croatia declared independence in 1991, and Bosnia–Herzegovina followed in 1992, while Montenegro remained in a federation with Serbia, officially called Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The ensuing Croatian War of Independence included limited naval engagements and a blockade of Croatia's coast by the Yugoslav Navy, leading to the Battle of the Dalmatian channels and a later withdrawal of Yugoslav vessels.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Montenegro declared itself independent in 2006, effectively land-locking Serbia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The period also saw the Adriatic Sea as the theatre of several NATO operations, including the blockade of Yugoslavia, intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina and the 1999 bombing of Yugoslavia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Italy and Yugoslavia defined their Adriatic continental shelf delimitation in 1968, with an additional agreement signed in 1975 on the Gulf of Trieste boundary, following the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The boundary agreed in 1968 extends 353 nautical miles (654 km; 406 mi) and consists of 43 points connected by straight lines or circular arc segments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The additional boundary agreed upon in 1975 consists of 5 points, extending from an end point of the 1968 line.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] All successor states of former Yugoslavia accepted the agreements.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the Adriatic's southernmost areas the border was not determined in order to avoid prejudicing the location of the tripoint with the Albanian continental shelf border, which remains undefined.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Before the breakup of Yugoslavia, Albania, Italy and Yugoslavia initially proclaimed 15-nautical-mile (28 km; 17 mi) territorial waters, subsequently reduced to international-standard 12 nautical miles (22 km; 14 mi) and all sides adopted baseline systems (mostly in the 1970s).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Albania and Italy determined their sea border in 1992 according to the equidistance principle.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Following Croatian EU membership, the Adriatic became an internal sea of the EU.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea defines the Adriatic Sea as an enclosed or semi-enclosed sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic Euroregion was established in Pula in 2006 to promote trans-regional and trans-national cooperation in the Adriatic Sea area and serve as an Adriatic framework to help resolve issues of regional importance.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In addition, the maritime boundary between Albania and Montenegro was not defined before the 1990s.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Croatia and Slovenia started negotiations to define maritime borders in the Gulf of Piran in 1992 but failed to agree, resulting in a dispute.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Both countries also declared their economic zones, which partially overlap.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Croatia's application to become an EU member state was initially suspended pending resolution of its border disputes with Slovenia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] These disputes with Slovenia were eventually settled with an agreement to accept the decision of an international arbitration commission set up via the UN, enabling Croatia to progress towards EU membership.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Croatia is still not following the resolution of the international arbitration for the Gulf of Piran.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] A dispute over the gulf is still on going with the Croatians handing out fines to Slovenian fishermen that are following the agreed economic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Aside from the EU membership difficulty, even before its settling the dispute has caused no major practical problems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The maritime boundary between Bosnia–Herzegovina and Croatia was formally settled in 1999, but a few issues are still in dispute—the Klek peninsula and two islets in the border area.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Croatia–Montenegro maritime boundary is disputed in the Bay of Kotor, at the Prevlaka peninsula.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] This dispute was exacerbated by the peninsula's occupation by the Yugoslav People's Army and later by the (Serbian–Montenegrin) FR Yugoslav Army, which in turn was replaced by a United Nations observer mission that lasted until 2002.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Croatia took over the area with an agreement that allowed Montenegrin presence in the bay's Croatian waters, and the dispute has become far less contentious since Montenegro's independence in 2006.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic Sea fishery's production is distributed among countries in the basin.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2000, the nominal—on a live weight basis—total landings of all Adriatic fisheries reached 110,000 tonnes (108,000 long tons).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Overfishing is a recognised problem—450 species of fish live in the Adriatic Sea, including 120 species threatened by excessive commercial fishing, a problem exacerbated by pollution and global warming.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Overexploited species include common dentex, red scorpionfish, monkfish, John Dory, blue shark, spiny dogfish, mullet, red mullet, Norway lobster, as well as European hake, and sardines.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Turtles and common bottlenose dolphins are also being killed by fishing nets.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The depleted fish stock, and Croatia's Ecological and Fisheries Protection Zone (ZERP) contributed to accusations of overfishing exchanged between Italian and Croatian fishermen.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] ZERP was introduced in 2003, but its application to EU member states was suspended in 2004.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The depleted stocks of fish are being addressed through a new proposed EU fisheries policy that was scheduled to take effect in 2013, when Croatia acceded to the EU, and restore the stocks to sustainable levels by 2015.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The largest volume of fish harvesting was in Italy, where the total production volume in 2007 stood at 465,637 tonnes (458,283 long tons).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2003, 28.8% of Italian fisheries production volume was generated in the Northern and central Adriatic, and 24.5% in Apulia (from the Southern Adriatic and Ionian Sea).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Italian fisheries, including those operating outside the Adriatic, employed 60,700 in the primary sector, including aquaculture (which comprises 40% of the total fisheries production).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The total fisheries output's gross value in 2002 was $1.9 billion.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2007, Croatia's production in live weight reached 53,083 tonnes (52,245 long tons).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2006, the total Croatian fisheries production volume was 37,800 tonnes (37,200 long tons) of catch and 14,200 tonnes (14,000 long tons) from marine aquaculture.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Croatian fisheries employed approximately 20,000.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Croatian marine aquaculture production consisted of tuna (47.2%), oysters and mussels (28.2% combined) and bass and bream (24.6% combined).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2007, Albanian fisheries production amounted to 7,505 tonnes (7,386 long tons), including aquaculture production, which reached 1,970 tonnes (1,940 long tons) in 2006.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] At the same time, Slovenian fisheries produced a total of 2,500 tonnes (2,460 long tons) with 55% of the production volume originating in aquaculture, representing the highest ratio in the Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Finally, the Montenegrin fisheries production stood at 911 tonnes (897 long tons) in 2006, with only 11 tonnes coming from aquaculture.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2007, the fisheries production in Bosnia–Herzegovina reached volume of 9,625 and 2,463 tonnes (9,473 and 2,424 long tons) in Slovenia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The countries bordering the Adriatic Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The largest number of tourist overnight stays and the most numerous tourist accommodation facilities are recorded in Italy, especially in the Veneto region (around Venice).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Veneto is followed by the Emilia-Romagna region and by the Adriatic Croatian counties.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Croatian tourist facilities are further augmented by 21,000 nautical ports and moorings; nautical tourists are attracted to various types of marine protected areas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] As of January 2012, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 103 Italian Adriatic beaches and 29 marinas, 116 Croatian beaches and 19 marinas, 7 Slovenian beaches and 2 marinas, and 16 Montenegrin beaches.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Adriatic tourism is a significant source of income for these countries, especially in Croatia and Montenegro where the tourism income generated along the Adriatic coast represents the bulk of such income.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The direct contribution of travel and tourism to Croatia's GDP stood at 5.1% in 2011, with the total industry contribution estimated at 12.8% of the national GDP.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] For Montenegro, the direct contribution of tourism to the national GDP is 8.1%, with the total contribution to the economy at 17.2% of Montenegrin GDP.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Tourism in Adriatic Croatia has recently exhibited greater growth than in the other regions around the Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] There are nineteen Adriatic Sea ports (in four different countries) that each handles more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The largest cargo ports among them are the Port of Trieste (the largest Adriatic cargo port in Italy), the Port of Venice, the Port of Ravenna, the Port of Koper (the largest Slovenian port), the Port of Rijeka (the largest Croatian cargo port), and the Port of Brindisi.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The largest passenger ports in the Adriatic are the Port of Split (the largest Croatian passenger port) and ports in Ancona (the largest Italian passenger seaport in the Adriatic).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The largest seaport in Montenegro is the Port of Bar.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2010, the Northern Adriatic seaports of Trieste, Venice, Ravenna, Koper and Rijeka founded the North Adriatic Ports Association to position themselves more favourably in the EU's transport systems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The port of Trieste is of particular importance for Central Europe because this is where the Transalpine Pipeline begins, supplying 100 percent of southern Germany, 90 percent of Austria and 50 percent of the Czech Republic with crude oil.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Natural gas is produced through several projects, including a joint venture of the Eni and INA companies that operates two platforms—one is in Croatian waters and draws gas from six wells, and the other (which started operating in 2010) is located in Italian waters.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic gas fields were discovered in the 1970s, but their development commenced in 1996.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In 2008, INA produced 14.58 million BOE per day of gas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] About 100 offshore platforms are located in the Emilia-Romagna region, along with 17 in the Northern Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Eni estimated its concessions in the Adriatic Sea to hold at least 40,000,000,000 cubic metres (1.4×1012 cu ft) of natural gas, adding that they may even reach 100,000,000,000 cubic metres (3.5×1012 cu ft).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] INA estimates, however, are 50% lower than those supplied by Eni.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Oil was discovered in the Northern Adriatic at a depth of approximately 5,400 metres (17,700 ft); the discovery was assessed as not viable because of its location, depth and quality.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] These gas and oil reserves are part of the Po basin Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Mediterranean Sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In the 2000s, investigation works aimed at discovering gas and oil reserves in the Middle and Southern Adriatic basins intensified, and by the decade's end, oil and natural gas reserves were discovered southeast of the Bari, Brindisi—Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Surveys indicate reserves of 3 billion barrels of oil in place and 5.7×1010 cubic metres (2,000,000,000,000 cu ft) of gas in place.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] The discovery was followed by further surveys off the Croatian coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] In January 2012, INA commenced prospecting for oil off Dubrovnik, marking the resumption of oil exploration along the eastern Adriatic coast after surveys commenced in the late 1980s around the island of Brač were cancelled because of Yugoslavia's breakup and war in Croatia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] Montenegro is also expected to look for oil off its coast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/adriatic-p02] As of January 2012, only 200 exploration wells had been sunk off the Croatian coast, with all but 30 in the Northern Adriatic basin.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Age class structures can be used to model population structures of many species including vertebrates, invertebrates, and vegetation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Factors that influence age class structures include birth rates, death rates, migration, and environmental stressors.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] These models allow for the prediction of growth or decline in a population based on current conditions or future management practices.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Age class structures can be used to help focus management on a certain age class to obtain the desires population size outcomes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Individuals in a population that are within a certain age range belong to the same class.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] These age classes count age like we usually do: individuals who are less than 1 year old are considered age class 0, those who are at least one year old but not yet two are age 1, and so on.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] When individuals are sorted into age classes like this, we can describe the population's age structure - meaning how many individuals are in each age group.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Imagine a species where no one lives past 3 years old.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This means all individuals would be either less than 1 year old (age class 0), 2 years old (age class 1), or 3 years old (age class 2).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Therefore, if there are 20 individuals in total - 4 are newborns, 6 are 1-year-olds, and 10 are 2-year-olds - then the age structure would be 0.2 in age class 0, 0.3 in age class 1, and 0.5 in age class 2.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] A stable age distribution happens when birth and death rates remain the same over time.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This creates a steady, balanced number of individuals in each age group.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] The age class structure will look like a rectangle when shown in a population pyramid, meaning there is a similar number of individuals in each age range.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] An unstable age distribution happens when birth or death rates change significantly, causing the number of individuals in each age group to shift.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This can make the population chart look uneven - like a triangle or an inverted triangle - showing that some age groups have many more or fewer individuals than others.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] For example, when managing a population of white tail deer targeting a specific age and sex can alter the population pyramid type to either increase, decrease, or stabilize population growth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] If you start off with a rapid growth age class structure, then targeting the juveniles who are not reproductive yet will help stabilize the population to a slower growth or no growth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This will make the number of juvenile females to closer the number of females who are aging out of the reproductive age.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Targeting a specific sex will also alter the age class data.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] If looking to reduce the population then targeting hunting efforts on females will have a more impactful change.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Removal of older individuals and males will increase the population by opening up resources for reproductive females and juveniles.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Age can be determined by counting growth rings in fish scales, otoliths, cross-sections of fin spines for species with thick spines such as triggerfish, or teeth for a few species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Each method has its merits and drawbacks.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Fish scales are easiest to obtain, but may be unreliable if scales have fallen off the fish and new ones grown in their places.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Fin spines may be unreliable for the same reason, and most fish do not have spines of sufficient thickness for clear rings to be visible.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Otoliths will have stayed with the fish throughout its life history, but obtaining them requires killing the fish.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Also, otoliths often require more preparation before ageing can occur.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] An example of using age class structure to learn about a population is a regular bell curve for the population of 1-5 year-old fish with a very low population for the 3-year-olds.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] An age class structure with gaps in population size like the one described earlier implies a bad spawning year 3 years ago in that species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Often fish in younger age class structures have very low numbers because they were small enough to slip through the sampling nets, and may in fact have a very healthy population.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This could skew class structure data and result in imaccurate management techniques.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Growing evidence suggests temporal shifts in body size, often studied with respect to climate and Bergmann's rule, may be explained by shifts in the age structure of a population.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Because individuals change in size and shape as they age, changes in age class structure can result in shifts in the morphospace of a population reflecting either a greater proportion of older (and larger) or younger (and smaller) individuals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Aging trees is performed through several methods, the first being to count the trees annual growth rings and the second is to calculate using the growth factor and circumference.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] After a wildfire, depending on the severity, some of the forest will experience a loss in the population of several species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This interference can drastically alter an age class structure.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] If the fire was low intensity and burned low to the ground killing only young trees, then the age structure would be heavily skewed towards having many older mature trees and very few young trees.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] Wild fires can alter age class structures by removing individuals in certain age classes and altering the type of population pyramid the species is experiencing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/age-class-structure] This shift in age class structures can also help predict how quickly the forest will rebound from the disturbance.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based models have many applications in biology, primarily due to the characteristics of the modeling method.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling is a rule-based, computational modeling methodology that focuses on rules and interactions among the individual components or the agents of the matrix .
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The goal of this modeling method is to generate populations of the system components of interest and simulate their interactions in a virtual world.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based models start with rules for behavior and seek to reconstruct, through computational instantiation of those behavioral rules, the observed patterns of behavior.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The behavior of an agent-based model is defined by the rules of its agents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Existing agent rules can be modified or new agents can be added without having to modify the entire model.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Through the use of the individual agents that interact locally with rules of behavior, agent-based models result in a synergy that leads to a higher level whole with much more intricate behavior than those of each individual agent.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Either by excluding non-essential details or when details are not available, agent-based models can be constructed in the absence of complete knowledge of the system under study.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] This allows the model to be as simple and verifiable as possible.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Biological systems exhibit behavior that appears to be random.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The probability of a particular behavior can be determined for a system as a whole and then be translated into rules for the individual agents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] In an ecological context, agent-based modeling can be used to model the behaviour of different species such as insects infestations, other invasive species, aphids, aquatic populations, and the evolution of innate foraging behaviors.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling has been used to simulate attack behavior of the mountain pine beetle (MPB), *Dendroctonus ponderosae*, in order to evaluate how different harvesting policies influence spatial characteristics of the forest and spatial propagation of the MPB infestation over time.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] About two-thirds of the land in British Columbia, Canada is covered by forests that are constantly being modified by natural disturbances such as fire, disease, and insect infestation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Forest resources make up approximately 15% of the province's economy, so infestations caused by insects such as the MPB can have significant impacts on the economy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The MPB outbreaks are considered a major natural disturbance that can result in widespread mortality of the lodgepole pine tree, one of the most abundant commercial tree species in British Columbia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Insect outbreaks have resulted in the death of trees over areas of several thousand square kilometers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based model developed for this study was designed to simulate the MPB attack behavior in order to evaluate how management practices influence the spatial distribution and patterns of insect population and their preferences for attacked and killed trees.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Three management strategies were considered by the model: 1) no management, 2) sanitation harvest and 3) salvage harvest.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] In the model, the Beetle Agent represented the MPB behavior; the Pine Agent represented the forest environment and tree health evolution; the Forest Management Agent represented the different management strategies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Beetle Agent follows a series of rules to decide where to fly within the forest and to select a healthy tree to attack, feed, and breed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The MPB typically kills host trees in its natural environment in order to successfully reproduce.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The beetle larvae feed on the inner bark of mature host trees, eventually killing them.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] In order for the beetles to reproduce, the host tree must be sufficiently large and have thick inner bark.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The MPB outbreaks end when the food supply decreases to the point that there is not enough to sustain the population or when climatic conditions become unfavorable for the beetle.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Pine Agent simulates the resistance of the host tree, specifically the Lodgepole pine tree, and monitors the state and attributes of each stand of trees.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] At some point in the MPB attack, the number of beetles per tree reaches the host tree capacity.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] When this point is reached, the beetles release a chemical to direct beetles to attack other trees.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Pine Agent models this behavior by calculating the beetle population density per stand and passes the information to the Beetle Agents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Forest Management Agent was used, at the stand level, to simulate two common silviculture practices (sanitation and salvage) as well as the strategy where no management practice was employed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] With the sanitation harvest strategy, if a stand has an infestation rate greater than a set threshold, the stand is removed as well as any healthy neighbor stand when the average size of the trees exceeded a set threshold.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] For the salvage harvest strategy, a stand is removed even it is not under a MPB attack if a predetermined number of neighboring stands are under a MPB attack.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study considered a forested area in the North-Central Interior of British Columbia of approximately 560 hectare.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The area consisted primarily of Lodgepole pine with smaller proportions of Douglas fir and White spruce.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was executed for five time steps, each step representing a single year.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Thirty simulation runs were conducted for each forest management strategy considered.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results of the simulation showed that when no management strategy was employed, the highest overall MPB infestation occurred.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results also showed that the salvage harvest management technique resulted in a 25% reduction in the number of forest strands killed by the MPB, as opposed to a 19% reduction by the sanitation harvest management strategy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] In summary, the results show that the model can be used as a tool to build forest management policies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Invasive species refers to "non-native" plants and animals that adversely affect the environments they invade.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The introduction of invasive species may have environmental, economic, and ecological implications.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based model developed for the study considered three types of agents: invasive species, importers, and border enforcement agents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] In the model, the invasive species can only react to their surroundings, while the importers and border enforcement agents are able to make their own decisions based on their own goals and objectives.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The invasive species has the ability to determine if it has been released in an area containing the target crop, and to spread to adjacent plots of the target crop.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model incorporates spatial probability maps that are used to determine if an invasive species becomes established.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study focused on shipments of broccoli from Mexico into California through the ports of entry Calexico, California and Otay Mesa, California.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The selected invasive species of concern was the crucifer flea beetle (*Phyllotreta cruciferae*).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] California is by far the largest producer of broccoli in the United States and so the concern and potential impact of an invasive species introduction through the chosen ports of entry is significant.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model also incorporated a spatially explicit damage function that was used to model invasive species damage in a realistic manner.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling provides the ability to analyze the behavior of heterogeneous actors, so three different types of importers were considered that differed in terms of commodity infection rates (high, medium, and low), pretreatment choice, and cost of transportation to the ports.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model gave predictions on inspection rates for each port of entry and importer and determined the success rate of border agent inspection, not only for each port and importer but also for each potential level of pretreatment (no pretreatment, level one, level two, and level three).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was implemented and ran in NetLogo, version 3.1.5.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Spatial information on the location of the ports of entry, major highways, and transportation routes was included in the analysis as well as a map of California broccoli crops layered with invasive species establishment probability maps.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] BehaviorSpace, a software tool integrated with NetLogo, was used to test the effects of different parameters (e.g. shipment value, pretreatment cost) in the model.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] On average, 100 iterations were calculated at each level of the parameter being used, where an iteration represented a one-year run.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results of the model showed that as inspection efforts increase, importers increase due care, or the pretreatment of shipments, and the total monetary loss of California crops decreases.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model showed that importers respond to an increase in inspection effort in different ways.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Some importers responded to increased inspection rate by increasing pretreatment effort, while others chose to avoid shipping to a specific port, or shopped for another port.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Another interesting outcome of the model is that when inspectors were not able to learn to respond to an importer with previously infested shipments, damage to California broccoli crops was estimated to be $150 million.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] However, when inspectors were able to increase inspection rates of importers with previous violations, damage to the California broccoli crops was reduced by approximately 12%.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model provides a mechanism to predict the introduction of invasive species from agricultural imports and their likely damage.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Equally as important, the model provides policy makers and border control agencies with a tool that can be used to determine the best allocation of inspectional resources.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] An agent-based model can be used to study the population dynamics of the bird cherry-oat aphid, *Rhopalosiphum padi*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study was conducted in a five square kilometer region of North Yorkshire, a county located in the Yorkshire and the Humber region of England.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based modeling method was chosen because of its focus on the behavior of the individual agents rather than the population as a whole.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The authors propose that traditional models that focus on populations as a whole do not take into account the complexity of the concurrent interactions in ecosystems, such as reproduction and competition for resources which may have significant impacts on population trends.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based modeling approach also allows modelers to create more generic and modular models that are more flexible and easier to maintain than modeling approaches that focus on the population as a whole.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Other proposed advantages of agent-based models include realistic representation of a phenomenon of interest due to the interactions of a group of autonomous agents, and the capability to integrate quantitative variables, differential equations, and rule based behavior into the same model.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was implemented in the modeling toolkit Repast using the JAVA programming language.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was run in daily time steps and focused on the autumn and winter seasons.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Input data for the model included habitat data, daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures, and wind speed and direction.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] For the Aphid agents, age, position, and morphology (alate or apterous) were considered.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Age ranged from 0.00 to 2.00, with 1.00 being the point at which the agent becomes an adult.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Reproduction by the Aphid agents is dependent on age, morphology, and daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Once nymphs hatch, they remain in the same location as their parents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The morphology of the nymphs is related to population density and the nutrient quality of the aphid's food source.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model also considered mortality among the Aphid agents, which is dependent on age, temperatures, and quality of habitat.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The speed at which an Aphid agent ages is determined by the daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model considered movement of the Aphid agents to occur in two separate phases, a migratory phase and a foraging phase, both of which affect the overall population distribution.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study started the simulation run with an initial population of 10,000 alate aphids distributed across a grid of 25 meter cells.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The simulation results showed that there were two major population peaks, the first in early autumn due to an influx of alate immigrants and the second due to lower temperatures later in the year and a lack of immigrants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Ultimately, it is the goal of the researchers to adapt this model to simulate broader ecosystems and animal types.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] A model is proposed to study the population dynamics of two species of macrophytes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Aquatic plants play a vital role in the ecosystems in which they live as they may provide shelter and food for other aquatic organisms.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] However, they may also have harmful impacts such as the excessive growth of non-native plants or eutrophication of the lakes in which they live leading to anoxic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Given these possibilities, it is important to understand how the environment and other organisms affect the growth of these aquatic plants to allow mitigation or prevention of these harmful impacts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The area of interest in the model was a lake in the Netherlands named Lake Veluwe.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] It is a relatively shallow lake with an average depth of 1.55 meters and covers about 30 square kilometers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The lake is under eutrophication stress which means that nutrients are not a limiting factor for either of the plant agents in the model.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The initial position of the plant agents in the model was randomly determined.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was implemented using Repast software package and was executed to simulate the growth and decay of the two different plant agents, taking into account the environmental agents previously discussed as well as interactions with other plant agents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results of the model execution show that the population distribution of *Chara aspera* has a spatial pattern very similar to the GIS maps of observed distributions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The authors of the study conclude that the agent rules developed in the study are reasonable to simulate the spatial pattern of macrophyte growth in this particular lake.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling is increasingly used to model the behaviour of individual cells within a tissue.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] These models are divided into on- and off-lattice models with on-lattice models such as cellular automata and cellular potts model and off-lattice models such as center-based models, vertex-based models, immersed boundary method models and models based on the subcellular element method.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] An agent-based model can be used model the colonisation of bacteria onto a surface, leading to the formation of biofilms.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Examining such formations is important in soil and river studies, dental hygiene studies, infectious disease and medical implant related infection research, and for understanding biocorrosion.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] An agent-based modelling paradigm was employed to make it possible to explore how each individual bacterium, of a particular species, contributes to the development of the biofilm.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The initial illustration of iDynoMiCS considered how environmentally fluctuating oxygen availability affects the diversity and composition of a community of denitrifying bacteria that induce the denitrification pathway under anoxic or low oxygen conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study explores the hypothesis that the existence of diverse strategies of denitrification in an environment can be explained by solely assuming that faster response incurs a higher cost.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based model suggests that if metabolic pathways can be switched without cost the faster the switching the better.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] However, where faster switching incurs a higher cost, there is a strategy with optimal response time for any frequency of environmental fluctuations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] This suggests that different types of denitrifying strategies win in different biological environments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Since this introduction the applications of iDynoMiCS continues to increase: a recent exploration of the plasmid invasion in biofilms being one example.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] This study explored the hypothesis that poor plasmid spread in biofilms is caused by a dependence of conjugation on the growth rate of the plasmid donor agent.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Through simulation, the paper suggests that plasmid invasion into a resident biofilm is only limited when plasmid transfer depends on growth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Sensitivity analysis techniques were employed that suggests parameters relating to timing (lag before plasmid transfer between agents) and spatial reach are more important for plasmid invasion into a biofilm than the receiving agents growth rate or probability of segregational loss.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Further examples that use iDynoMiCS continue to be published, including use of iDynoMiCS in modelling of a *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* biofilm with glucose substrate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] iDynoMiCS has been developed by an international team of researchers in order to provide a common platform for further development of all individual-based models of microbial biofilms and such like.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was originally the result of years of work by Laurent Lardon, Brian Merkey, and Jan-Ulrich Kreft, with code contributions from Joao Xavier.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] With additional funding from the National Centre for Replacement, Refinement, and Reduction of Animals in Research (NC3Rs) in 2013, the development of iDynoMiCS as a tool for biological exploration continues apace, with new features being added when appropriate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] From its inception, the team have committed to releasing iDynoMiCS as an open source platform, encouraging collaborators to develop additional functionality that can then be merged into the next stable release.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] IDynoMiCS has been implemented in the Java programming language, with MATLAB and R scripts provided to analyse results.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Biofilm structures that are formed in simulation can be viewed as a movie using POV-Ray files that are generated as the simulation is run.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Experiments have shown that exposure to ionizing irradiation of pubertal mammary glands results in an increase in the ratio of mammary stem cells in the gland.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] This is important because stem cells are thought to be key targets for cancer initiation by ionizing radiation because they have the greatest long-term proliferative potential and mutagenic events persist in multiple daughter cells.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Additionally, epidemiology data show that children exposed to ionizing radiation have a substantially greater breast cancer risk than adults.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The first agent-based model is a multiscale model of mammary gland development starting with a rudimentary mammary ductal tree at the onset of puberty (during active proliferation) all the way to a full mammary gland at adulthood (when there is little proliferation).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model consists of millions of agents, with each agent representing a mammary stem cell, a progenitor cell, or a differentiated cell in the breast.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Simulations were first run on the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory Lawrencium supercomputer to parameterize and benchmark the model against a variety of *in vivo* mammary gland measurements.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was then used to test the three different mechanisms to determine which one led to simulation results that matched *in vivo* experiments the best.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Surprisingly, radiation-induced cell inactivation by death did not contribute to increased stem cell frequency independently of the dose delivered in the model.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Instead the model revealed that the combination of increased self-renewal and cell proliferation during puberty led to stem cell enrichment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] In contrast epithelial-mesenchymal transition in the model was shown to increase stem cell frequency not only in pubertal mammary glands but also in adult glands.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] This latter prediction, however, contradicted the *in vivo* data; irradiation of adult mammary glands did not lead to increased stem cell frequency.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] These simulations therefore suggested self-renewal as the primary mechanism behind pubertal stem cell increase.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] To further evaluate self-renewal as the mechanism, a second agent-based model was created to simulate the growth dynamics of human mammary epithelial cells (containing stem/progenitor and differentiated cell subpopulations) *in vitro* after irradiation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] By comparing the simulation results with data from the *in vitro* experiments, the second agent-based model further confirmed that cells must extensively proliferate to observe a self-renewal dependent increase in stem/progenitor cell numbers after irradiation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] The combination of the two agent-based models and the *in vitro*/*in vivo* experiments provide insight into why children exposed to ionizing radiation have a substantially greater breast cancer risk than adults.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agent-based-model-in-biology] Together, they support the hypothesis that the breast is susceptible to a transient increase in stem cell self-renewal when exposed to radiation during puberty, which primes the adult tissue to develop cancer decades later.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Studies of business growth and performance in farming have found that successful agricultural businesses are cost-efficient internally and operate in favourable economic, political, and physical-organic environments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They are able to expand and make profits, improve the productivity of land, labor, and capital, and keep their costs down to ensure market price competitiveness.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It encompasses a broader spectrum through the agribusiness system which includes input supplies, value-addition, marketing, entrepreneurship, microfinancing, and agricultural extension.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In some countries like the Philippines, creation and management of agribusiness enterprises require consultation with registered agriculturists above a certain level of operations, capitalization, land area, or number of animals in the farm.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The word "agribusiness" is a portmanteau of the words *agriculture* and *business.* The earliest known use of the word was in the Volume 155 of the Canadian Almanac & Directory published in 1847.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Their book argued against the New Deal programs of then U.S.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] President Franklin Roosevelt as it led to the increase in agricultural prices.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Davis and Goldberg favored corporate-driven agriculture or large-scale farming to revolutionize the agriculture sector, lessening the dependency on state power and politics.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They explained in the book that vertically integrated firms within the agricultural value chains have the ability to control prices and where they are distributed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Goldberg then assisted in the establishment of the first undergraduate program in agribusiness in 1966 at the UP College of Agriculture in Los Baños, Philippines as Bachelor of Science in Agriculture major in Agribusiness.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The program was initially a joint undertaking with the UP College of Business Administration in Diliman, Quezon City until 1975.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Drilon of the University of the Philippines then published the book "*Agribusiness Management Resource Materials*" (1971) which would be the foundation of current agribusiness programs around the world.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In 1973, Drilon and Goldberg further expanded the concept of agribusiness to include support organizations such as governments, research institutions, schools, financial institutions, and cooperatives within the integrated Agribusiness System.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Shultz II (2005) of Loyola University Chicago reframed the definition of agribusiness to emphasize its lack of focus on farm production but towards market centricity and innovative approach to serve consumers worldwide.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Boland defined the unique economic characteristics of agribusiness supply chains from industrial manufacturing and service supply chains.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In 2017, noting the rise of genetic engineering and biotechnology in agriculture, Goldberg further expanded the definition of agribusiness which covers all the interdependent aspects of the food system including medicine, nutrition, and health.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] He also emphasized the responsibility of agribusiness to be environmentally and socially conscious towards sustainability.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Some agribusinesses have adopted the triple bottom line framework such as aligning for fair trade, organic, good agricultural practices, and B-corporation certifications towards the concept of social entrepreneurship.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The term value chain was first popularized in a book published in 1985 by Michael Porter, who used it to illustrate how companies could achieve what he called “competitive advantage” by adding value within their organization.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Subsequently, the term was adopted for agricultural development purposes and has now become very much in vogue among those working in this field, with most bilateral and multilateral aid organisations using it to guide their development interventions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] At the heart of the agricultural value chain concept is the idea of actors connected along a chain producing and delivering goods to consumers through a sequence of activities.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] However, this “vertical” chain cannot function in isolation and an important aspect of the value chain approach is that it also considers “horizontal” impacts on the chain, such as input and finance provision, extension support and the general enabling environment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The approach has been found useful, particularly by donors, in that it has resulted in a consideration of all those factors impacting on the ability of farmers to access markets profitably, leading to a broader range of chain interventions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It is used both for upgrading existing chains and for donors to identify market opportunities for small farmers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] An agricultural supply store or agrocenter is an agriculturally-oriented shop where one sells agricultural supplies — inputs required for agricultural production such as pesticides, feed and fertilizers .
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Sometimes these stores are organized as cooperatives, where store customers aggregate their resources to purchase agricultural inputs.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural supply and the stores that provide it are part of the larger Agribusiness industry.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] A farmworker or farmhand, is someone employed for labor in agriculture.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In labor law, the term "farmworker" is sometimes used more narrowly, applying only to a hired worker involved in agricultural production, including harvesting.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural work varies widely depending on context, degree of mechanization and crop.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Low wages for farmworkers have been associated with farmworker shortages and delayed adoption of agricultural technology.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural labor is often affected by the human health impacts of environmental issues related to agriculture, such as health effects of pesticides or exposure to other health challenges such as valley fever.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] To address these environmental concerns and marginal working conditions, many labor rights, economic justice and environmental justice movements have been organized or supported by farmworkers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Irrigation in agriculture is the practice of applying controlled amounts of water to land to help grow crops, landscape plants, and lawns.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Irrigation has been a key aspect of agriculture for over 5,000 years and has been developed by many cultures worldwide.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Irrigation helps to grow crops, maintain landscapes, and revegetate disturbed soils in dry areas and during times of below-average rainfall.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In addition to these uses, irrigation is also employed to protect crops from frost, suppress weed growth in grain fields, and prevent soil consolidation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It is also used to cool livestock, reduce dust, dispose of sewage, and support mining operations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Drainage, which involves the removal of surface and sub-surface water from a given location, is often studied in conjunction with irrigation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Irrigation and drainage improvements are not necessarily mutually exclusive.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Often both may be required together to assure sustained high-level production of crops.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] For a discussion of the role of drainage practices in agriculture .
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Several irrigation methods differ in how water is supplied to plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Surface irrigation, also known as gravity irrigation, is the oldest form of irrigation and has been in use for thousands of years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In sprinkler irrigation, water is piped to one or more central locations within the field and distributed by overhead high-pressure water devices.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation is a system that distributes water under low pressure through a piped network and applies it as a small discharge to each plant.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation uses less pressure and water flow than sprinkler irrigation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Drip irrigation delivers water directly to the root zone of plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Subirrigation has been used in field crops in areas with high water tables for many years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It involves artificially raising the water table to moisten the soil below the root zone of plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Irrigation water can come from groundwater (extracted from springs or by using wells), from surface water (withdrawn from rivers, lakes or reservoirs) or from non-conventional sources like treated wastewater, desalinated water, drainage water, or fog collection.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Irrigation can be supplementary to rainfall, which is common in many parts of the world as rainfed agriculture, or it can be full irrigation, where crops rarely rely on any contribution from rainfall.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Full irrigation is less common and occurs only in arid landscapes with very low rainfall or when crops are grown in semi-arid areas outside the rainy season.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The environmental effects of irrigation relate to the changes in quantity and quality of soil and water as a result of irrigation and the subsequent effects on natural and social conditions in river basins and downstream of an irrigation scheme.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The effects stem from altered hydrological conditions resulting from the installation and operation of the irrigation scheme.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Amongst these problems is the depletion of underground aquifers through overdrafting.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Soil can be over-irrigated due to poor distribution uniformity or management wastes water, chemicals, and may lead to water pollution.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Over-irrigation can cause deep drainage from rising water tables, which can lead to irrigation salinity problems, requiring watertable control through some form of subsurface land drainage.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Seed companies produce and sell seeds for flowers, fruits and vegetables to commercial growers and amateur gardeners.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The production of seed is a multibillion-dollar global business, which uses growing facilities and growing locations worldwide.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] While most of the seed is produced by large specialist growers, large amounts are also produced by small growers who produce only one to a few crop types.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The larger companies supply seed both to commercial resellers and wholesalers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The resellers and wholesalers sell to vegetable and fruit growers, and to companies who package seed into packets and sell them on to the amateur gardener.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Most seed companies or resellers that sell to retail produce a catalog, for seed to be sown the following spring, that is generally published during early winter.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] These catalogs are eagerly awaited by the amateur gardener, as during winter months there is little that can be done in the garden so this time can be spent planning the following year’s gardening.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The largest collection of nursery and seed trade catalogs in the U.S. is held at the National Agricultural Library where the earliest catalogs date from the late 18th century, with most published from the 1890s to the present.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Seed companies produce a huge range of seeds from highly developed F1 hybrids to open pollinated wild species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They have extensive research facilities to produce plants with genetic materials that result in improved uniformity and appeal.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] These qualities might include disease resistance, higher yields, dwarf habit and vibrant or new colors.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] These improvements are often closely guarded to protect them from being utilized by other producers, thus plant cultivars are often sold under the company's own name and protected by international laws from being grown for seed production by others.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Along with the growth in the allotment movement, and the increasing popularity of gardening, there have emerged many small independent seed companies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Many of these are active in seed conservation and encouraging diversity.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They often offer organic and open pollinated varieties of seeds as opposed to hybrids.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Many of these varieties are heirloom varieties.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The use of old varieties maintains diversity in the horticultural gene pool.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It may be more appropriate for amateur gardeners to use older (heirloom) varieties as the modern seed types are often the same as those grown by commercial producers, and so characteristics which are useful to them (e.g. vegetables ripening at the same time) may be unsuited to home growing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] A fertilizer or fertiliser is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soil or to plant tissues to supply plant nutrients.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Fertilizers may be distinct from liming materials or other non-nutrient soil amendments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Many sources of fertilizer exist, both natural and industrially produced.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] For most modern agricultural practices, fertilization focuses on three main macronutrients: nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) with occasional addition of supplements like rock flour for micronutrients.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Farmers apply these fertilizers in a variety of ways: through dry or pelletized or liquid application processes, using large agricultural equipment, or hand-tool methods.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Historically, fertilization came from natural or organic sources: compost, animal manure, human manure, harvested minerals, crop rotations, and byproducts of human-nature industries (e.g. fish processing waste, or bloodmeal from animal slaughter).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] However, starting in the 19th century, after innovations in plant nutrition following Justus von Liebig's discoveries, an agricultural industry developed around synthetically created agrochemical fertilizers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] This transition was important in transforming the global food system towards larger-scale industrial agriculture with large crop yields in monocultures.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The invention of Haber process for producing ammonia for nitrogen in the 20th century combined with amplified chemical production capacity created during World War II led to a boom in using nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In the latter half of the 20th century, increased use of nitrogen fertilizers (800% increase between 1961 and 2019) has been a crucial component of the increased productivity of conventional food systems as part of the so-called "Green Revolution".
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Fertilizers, especially when applied excessively, can have environmental consequences such as water pollution and eutrophication due to nutrient runoff.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Additionally, the chemical process for creating the fertilizers results in byproducts, including carbon and other emissions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In some cases contamination and pollution of soil result by accumulation of heavy metals contained in some fertilizers collected through mining.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Sustainable agricultural practices, such as reduced tillage and planting buffer strips, can minimize these adverse environmental effects.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] A farm (also called an agricultural holding) is an area of land that is devoted primarily to agricultural processes with the primary objective of producing food and other crops; it is the basic facility in food production.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The name is used for specialized units such as arable farms, vegetable farms, fruit farms, dairy, pig and poultry farms, and land used for the production of natural fiber, biofuel, and other biobased products.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It includes ranches, feedlots, orchards, plantations and estates, smallholdings, and hobby farms, and includes the farmhouse and agricultural buildings as well as the land.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In modern times, the term has been extended to include such industrial operations as wind farms and fish farms, both of which can operate on land or at sea.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] There are about 570 million farms in the world, most of which are small and family-operated.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Small farms with a land area of fewer than 2 hectares operate on about 12% of the world's agricultural land, and family farms comprise about 75% of the world's agricultural land.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Modern farms in developed countries are highly mechanized.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In the United States, livestock may be raised on rangeland and finished in feedlots, and the mechanization of crop production has brought about a great decrease in the number of agricultural workers needed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In Europe, traditional family farms are giving way to larger production units.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In Australia, some farms are very large because the land is unable to support a high stocking density of livestock because of climatic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In less developed countries, small farms are the norm, and the majority of rural residents are subsistence farmers, feeding their families and selling any surplus products in the local market.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] An agricultural engineer is an engineer with an agriculture background.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural engineers make the engineering designs and plans in an agricultural project, usually in partnership with an agriculturist who is more proficient in farming and agricultural science.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Primary food processing turns agricultural products, such as raw wheat kernels or livestock, into something that can eventually be eaten.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] This category includes ingredients that are produced by ancient processes such as drying, threshing, winnowing and milling grain, shelling nuts, and butchering animals for meat.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It also includes deboning and cutting meat, freezing and smoking fish and meat, extracting and filtering oils, canning food, preserving food through food irradiation, and candling eggs, as well as homogenizing and pasteurizing milk.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Contamination and spoilage problems in primary food processing can lead to significant public health threats, as the resulting foods are used so widely.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] However, many forms of processing contribute to improved food safety and longer shelf life before the food spoils.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Commercial food processing uses control systems such as hazard analysis and critical control points (HACCP) and failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) to reduce the risk of harm.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Secondary food processing is the everyday process of creating food from ingredients that are ready to use.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Baking bread, regardless of whether it is made at home, in a small bakery, or in a large factory, is an example of secondary food processing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Fermenting fish and making wine, beer, and other alcoholic products are traditional forms of secondary food processing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Sausages are a common form of secondary processed meat, formed by comminution (grinding) of meat that has already undergone primary processing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Most of the secondary food processing methods known to humankind are commonly described as cooking methods.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural marketing covers the services involved in moving an agricultural product from the farm to the consumer.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] These services involve the planning, organizing, directing and handling of agricultural produce in such a way as to satisfy farmers, intermediaries and consumers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Numerous interconnected activities are involved in doing this, such as planning production, growing and harvesting, grading, packing and packaging, transport, storage, agro- and food processing, provision of market information, distribution, advertising and sale.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Effectively, the term encompasses the entire range of supply chain operations for agricultural products, whether conducted through *ad hoc* sales or through a more integrated chain, such as one involving contract farming.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] A farmers' market (or farmers market according to the AP stylebook, also farmer's market in the Cambridge Dictionary) is a physical retail marketplace intended to sell foods directly by farmers to consumers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Farmers' markets may be indoors or outdoors and typically consist of booths, tables or stands where farmers sell their produce, live animals and plants, and sometimes prepared foods and beverages.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Farmers' markets exist in many countries worldwide and reflect the local culture and economy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The size of the market may be just a few stalls or it may be as large as several city blocks.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Due to their nature, they tend to be less rigidly regulated than retail produce shops.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They are distinguished from public markets, which are generally housed in permanent structures, open year-round, and offer a variety of non-farmer/non-producer vendors, packaged foods and non-food products.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural extension is the application of scientific research and new knowledge to agricultural practices through farmer education.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The field of 'extension' now encompasses a wider range of communication and learning activities organized for rural people by educators from different disciplines, including agriculture, agricultural marketing, health, and business studies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Extension practitioners can be found throughout the world, usually working for government agencies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They are represented by several professional organizations, networks and extension journals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural extension agencies in developing countries receive large amounts of support from international development organizations such as the World Bank and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] An agricultural cooperative, also known as a farmers' co-op, is a producer cooperative in which farmers pool their resources in certain areas of activities.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural production cooperatives include collective farms in former socialist countries, the kibbutzim in Israel, collectively-governed community shared agriculture, Longo Maï cooperatives in Costa Rica, France, and some other countries, CPAs in Cuba, and Nicaraguan production cooperatives.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In Southeast Asian developing countries such as Vietnam, agricultural cooperatives remain to play an important role in economic and social activities in rural areas, although they have relied mainly on government subsidies .
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Notable examples of agricultural cooperatives include Dairy Farmers Of America, the largest dairy company in the US, Amul, the largest food product marketing organization in India, and Zen-Noah, a federation of agricultural cooperatives that handles 70% of the sales of chemical fertilizers in Japan.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agricultural cooperatives are owned and democratically controlled by their members.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The governance structure can vary between the different types, but in general members elect representatives to a board of directors and contribute to organizational decision making through a democratic voting process.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) is a specialized agency of the United Nations that leads international efforts to defeat hunger and improve nutrition and food security.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Its Latin motto, *fiat panis*, translates to "let there be bread".
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It was founded on 16 October 1945 in Quebec City, Canada.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The FAO comprises 194 members, including 193 countries and one member organization, the European Union (EU).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Its headquarters is in Rome, Italy, and it maintains regional and field offices worldwide, operating in over 130 countries.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It helps governments and development agencies coordinate their activities to improve and develop agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and land and water resources.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It also conducts research, provides technical assistance to projects, operates educational and training programs, and collects agricultural output, production, and development data.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The FAO is governed by a biennial conference representing each member country and the EU, which elects a 49-member executive council.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] of China, serves as the chief administrative officer.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Various committees govern matters such as finance, programs, agriculture, and fisheries.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Obverse: Young woman with braid facing left.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Reverse: Cow nursing calf, face value & date.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] An agriculturist, agriculturalist, agrologist, or agronomist (abbreviated as agr.) is a professional in the science, practice, and management of agriculture and agribusiness.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] It is a regulated profession in Canada, Pakistan, India, Japan, the Philippines, the United States, and the European Union.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Other names used to designate the profession include agricultural scientist, agricultural manager, agricultural planner, agriculture researcher, or agriculture policy maker.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The primary role of agriculturists are in leading agricultural projects and programs, usually in agribusiness planning or research for the benefit of farms, food, and agribusiness-related organizations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agriculturists usually are designated in the government as public agriculturists serving as agriculture policymakers or technical advisors for policy making.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Preparation of technical engineering designs and construction for agriculture meanwhile are reserved for agricultural engineers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agriculturists may pursue environmental planning and focus on agricultural and rural planning.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Studies of agribusiness often come from the academic fields of agricultural economics and management studies, sometimes called agribusiness management.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] To promote more development of food economies, many government agencies support the research and publication of economic studies and reports exploring agribusiness and agribusiness practices.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Some of these studies are on foods produced for export and are derived from agencies focused on food exports.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] These agencies include the Foreign Agricultural Service (FAS) of the U.S.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Department of Agriculture, Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC), Austrade, and New Zealand Trade and Enterprise (NZTE).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] The Federation of International Trade Associations publishes studies and reports by FAS and AAFC, as well as other non-governmental organizations on its website.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In their book *A Concept of Agribusiness*, Ray Goldberg and John Davis provided a rigorous economic framework for the field.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] They traced a complex value-added chain that begins with the farmer's purchase of seed and livestock and ends with a product fit for the consumer's table.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] Agribusiness boundary expansion is driven by a variety of transaction costs.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] As concern over global warming intensifies, biofuels derived from crops are gaining increased public and scientific attention.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] This is driven by factors such as oil price spikes, the need for increased energy security, concern over greenhouse gas emissions from fossil fuels, and support from government subsidies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/agribusiness] In Europe and in the US, increased research and production of biofuels have been mandated by law.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Coastal regions, such as the Baltic Sea, the northern Gulf of Mexico, and the Chesapeake Bay, as well as large enclosed water bodies like Lake Erie, have been affected by deoxygenation due to eutrophication.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Excess nutrients are put into these systems by rivers, ultimately from urban and agricultural runoff and exacerbated by deforestation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] These nutrients lead to high productivity that produces organic material that sinks to the bottom and is respired.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The respiration of that organic material uses up the oxygen and causes hypoxia or anoxia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The UN Environment Programme reported 146 dead zones in 2004 in the world's oceans where marine life could not be supported due to depleted oxygen levels.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Some of these were as small as a square kilometer (0.4 mi2), but the largest dead zone covered 70,000 square kilometers (27,000 mi2).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] A 2008 study counted 405 dead zones worldwide.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Aquatic and marine dead zones can be caused by an increase in nutrients (particularly nitrogen and phosphorus) in the water, known as eutrophication.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] These nutrients are the fundamental building blocks of single-celled, plant-like organisms that live in the water column, and whose growth is limited in part by the availability of these materials.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] With more available nutrients, single-celled aquatic organisms (such as algae and cyanobacteria) have the resources necessary to exceed their previous growth limit and begin to multiply at an exponential rate.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Exponential growth leads to rapid increases in the density of certain types of these phytoplankton, a phenomenon known as an algal bloom.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The major groups of algae are cyanobacteria, green algae, dinoflagellates, coccolithophores and diatom algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] An increase in the input of nitrogen and phosphorus generally causes cyanobacteria to bloom.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Other algae are consumed and thus do not accumulate to the same extent as cyanobacteria.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Cyanobacteria are not good food for zooplankton and fish and hence accumulate in water, die, and then decompose.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The bacterial degradation of their biomass consumes the oxygen in the water, thereby creating the state of hypoxia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Dead zones can be caused by natural and by anthropogenic factors.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Natural causes include coastal upwelling, changes in wind, and water circulation patterns.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Other environmental factors that determine the occurrence or intensity of a dead zone include long water residence times, high temperatures, and high levels of sunlight penetration through the water column.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Additionally, natural oceanographic phenomena can cause deoxygenation of parts of the water column.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] For example, enclosed bodies of water, such as fjords or the Black Sea, have shallow sills at their entrances, causing water to be trapped there for a long time.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The eastern tropical Pacific Ocean and northern Indian Ocean have lowered oxygen concentrations which are thought to be in regions where there is minimal circulation to replace the oxygen that is consumed.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] These areas are also known as oxygen minimum zones (OMZ).
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In many cases, OMZs are permanent or semi-permanent areas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Remains of organisms found within sediment layers near the mouth of the Mississippi River indicate four hypoxic events before the advent of synthetic fertilizer.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In these sediment layers, anoxia-tolerant species are the most prevalent remains found.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The periods indicated by the sediment record correspond to historic records of high river flow recorded by instruments at Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Changes in ocean circulation triggered by ongoing climate change could also add or magnify other causes of oxygen reductions in the ocean.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Scientific studies of the water column, wind and discharge patterns near the mouths of the Mississippi and Atchafalaya Rivers has demonstrated certain exchanges of bottom water in the Texas-Louisiana shelf that might impact the dynamics within the dead zone.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Anthropogenic causes include use of chemical fertilizers and their subsequent presence in water runoff and groundwater, direct sewage discharge into rivers and lakes, and nutrient discharge into groundwater from large, accumulated quantities of animal waste.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Use of chemical fertilizers is considered the major human-related cause of dead zones around the world.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] However, runoff from sewage, urban land use, and fertilizers can also contribute to eutrophication.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In August 2017, a report suggested that the US meat industry and agroeconomic system are predominantly responsible for the largest-ever dead zone in the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Soil runoff and leached nitrate, exacerbated by agricultural land management and tillage practices as well as manure and synthetic fertilizer usage, contaminated water from the Heartland to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] A large portion of the plant matter by-products from crops grown in this region are used as major feed components in the production of meat animals for agribusiness companies, like Tyson and Smithfield Foods.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Over 86% of the livestock feed is inedible for humans.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Around the world, dead zones have developed in continental seas, such as the Baltic Sea, Kattegat, Black Sea, Gulf of Mexico, and East China Sea, all of which are major fishery areas.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The type of dead zone can, in some ways, be categorized by the time required for the water to return to full health.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] This time frame depends on the intensity of eutrophication and level of oxygen depletion.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] A water body that sinks to anoxic conditions and experiences extreme reduction in community diversity will have to travel a much longer path to return to full health.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] A water body that only experiences mild hypoxia and maintains community diversity and maturity will require a much shorter path length to return to full health.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The most notable effects of eutrophication are vegetal blooms, sometimes toxic, loss of biodiversity and anoxia, which can lead to the massive death of aquatic organisms.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Due to the hypoxic conditions present in dead zones, marine life within these areas tends to be scarce.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Most fish and motile organisms tend to emigrate out of the zone as oxygen concentrations fall, and benthic populations may experience severe losses when oxygen concentrations are below 0.5 mg l−1 O2.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In severe anoxic conditions, microbial life may experience dramatic shifts in community identity as well, resulting in an increased abundance of anaerobic organisms as aerobic microbes decrease in number and switch energy sources for oxidation such as nitrate, sulfate, or iron reduction.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Sulfur reduction is a particular concern as hydrogen sulfide is toxic and stresses most organisms within the zone further, exacerbating mortality risks.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Low oxygen levels can have severe effects on survivability of organisms inside the area while above lethal anoxic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Studies conducted along the Gulf Coast of North America have shown hypoxic conditions lead to reduction of reproductive rates and growth rates in a variety of organisms including fish and benthic invertebrates.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Organisms able to leave the area typically do so when oxygen concentrations decrease to less than 2 mg l−1.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] At these oxygen concentrations and below, organisms that survive inside the oxygen deficient environment and are unable to escape the area will often exhibit progressively worsening stress behavior and die.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Surviving organisms tolerant of hypoxic conditions often exhibit physiological adaptations appropriate for persisting within hypoxic environments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Examples of such adaptations include increased efficiency of oxygen intake and use, lowering required amount of oxygen intake through reduced growth rates or dormancy, and increasing the usage of anaerobic metabolic pathways.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Community composition in benthic communities is dramatically disrupted by periodic oxygen depletion events, such as those of seasonal dead zones and occurring as a result of diel cycles.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The longterm effects of such hypoxic conditions result in a shift in communities, most commonly manifest as a decrease in species diversity through mass mortality events.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Reestablishment of benthic communities depend upon composition of adjacent communities for larval recruitment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] This results in a shift towards faster establishing colonizers with shorter and more opportunistic life strategies, potentially disrupting historic benthic compositions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The influence of dead zones on fisheries and other marine commercial activities varies by the length of occurrence and location.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] However, studies estimate that the increased production in the surrounding areas do not offset the net decrease in productivity resulting from the dead zone.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] For instance, an estimated 17,000 MT of carbon in the form of prey for fisheries has been lost as a result of dead zones in the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Additionally, many stressors in fisheries are worsened by hypoxic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Indirect factors such as increased success by invasive species and increased pandemic intensity in stressed species such as oysters both lead to losses in revenue and ecological stability in affected regions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] There has been a severe increase in mass mortality events associated with low oxygen causing mass hypoxia with the majority having been in the last 2 decades.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The rise in water temperature leads to an increase in oxygen demand and the increase for ocean deoxygenation which causes these large coral reef dead zones.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] For many coral reefs, the response to this hypoxia is very dependent on the magnitude and duration of the deoxygenation.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The symptoms can be anywhere from reduced photosynthesis and calcification to bleaching.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Hypoxia can have indirect effects like the abundance of algae and spread of coral diseases in the ecosystems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] While coral is unable to handle such low levels of oxygen, algae is quite tolerant.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Because of this, in interaction zones between algae and coral, increased hypoxia will cause more coral death and higher spread of algae.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The increase mass coral dead zones is reinforced by the spread of coral diseases.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Coral diseases can spread easily when there are high concentrations of sulfide and hypoxic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Due to the loop of hypoxia and coral reef mortality, the fish and other marine life that inhabit the coral reefs have a change in behavioral in response to the hypoxia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Some fish will go upwards to find more oxygenated water, and some enter a phase of metabolic and ventilatory depression.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Invertebrates migrate out of their homes to the surface of substratum or move to the tips of arborescent coral colonies.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Around six million people, the majority who live in developing countries, depend on coral reef fisheries.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] These mass die-offs due to extreme hypoxic events can have severe impacts on reef fish populations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Coral reef ecosystems offer a variety of essential ecosystem services including shoreline protection, nitrogen fixation, and waste assimilation, and tourism opportunities.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The continued decline of oxygen in oceans on coral reefs is concerning because it takes many years (decades) to repair and regrow corals.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Despite most other life forms being killed by the lack of oxygen, jellyfish can thrive and are sometimes present in dead zones in vast numbers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Jellyfish blooms produce large quantities of mucus, leading to major changes in food webs in the ocean since few organisms feed on them.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The organic carbon in mucus is metabolized by bacteria which return it to the atmosphere in the form of carbon dioxide in what has been termed a "jelly carbon shunt".
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The potential worsening of jellyfish blooms as a result of human activities has driven new research into the influence of dead zones on jelly populations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The primary concern is the potential for dead zones to serve as breeding grounds for jelly populations as a result of the hypoxic conditions driving away competition for resources and common predators of jellyfish.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The increased population of jellyfish could have high commercial costs with loss of fisheries, destruction and contamination of trawling nets and fishing vessels, and lowered tourism revenue in coastal systems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Globally, seagrass has been declining rapidly.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] It is estimated that 21% of the 71 known seagrass species have decreasing population trends and 11% of those species have been designated as threatened on the ICUN Red List.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Hypoxia that leads to eutrophication caused from ocean deoxygenation is one of the main underlying factors of these die-offs.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Eutrophication causes enhanced nutrient enrichment which can result in seagrass productivity, but with continual nutrient enrichment in seagrass meadows, it can cause excessive growth of microalgae, epiphytes and phytoplankton resulting in hypoxic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Seagrass is both a source and a sink for oxygen in the surrounding water column and sediments.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] At night, the inner part of seagrass oxygen pressure is linearly related to the oxygen concentration in the water column, so low water column oxygen concentrations often result in hypoxic seagrass tissues, which can eventually kill off the seagrass.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Normally, seagrass sediments must supply oxygen to the below-ground tissue through either photosynthesis or by diffusing oxygen from the water column through leaves to rhizomes and roots.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] However, with the change in seagrass oxygen balances, it can often result in hypoxic seagrass tissues.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Seagrass exposed to this hypoxic water column show increased respiration, reduced rates of photosynthesis, smaller leaves, and reduced number of leaves per shoot.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] This causes insufficient supply of oxygen to the belowground tissues for aerobic respiration, so seagrass must rely on the less-efficient anaerobic respiration.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Seagrass die-offs create a positive feedback loop in which the mortality events cause more death as higher oxygen demands are created when dead plant material decomposes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Because hypoxia increases the invasion of sulfides in seagrass, this negatively affects seagrass through photosynthesis, metabolism and growth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Generally, seagrass is able to combat the sulfides by supplying enough oxygen to the roots.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] However, deoxygenation causes the seagrass to be unable to supply this oxygen, thus killing it off.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Deoxygenation reduces the diversity of organisms inhabiting seagrass beds by eliminating species that cannot tolerate the low oxygen conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Indirectly, the loss and degradation of seagrass threatens numerous species that rely on seagrass for either shelter or food.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The loss of seagrass also effects the physical characteristics and resilience of seagrass ecosystems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Seagrass beds provide nursery grounds and habitat to many harvested commercial, recreational, and subsistence fish and shellfish.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In many tropical regions, local people are dependent on seagrass associated fisheries as a source of food and income.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Seagrass also provides many ecosystem services including water purification, coastal protection, erosion control, sequestration and delivery of trophic subsidies to adjacent marine and terrestrial habitats.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Continued deoxygenation causes the effects of hypoxia to be compounded by climate change which will increase the decline in seagrass populations.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Compared to seagrass beds and coral reefs, hypoxia is more common on a regular basis in mangrove ecosystems, though ocean deoxygenation is compounding the negative effects by anthropogenic nutrient inputs and land use modification.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Like seagrass, mangrove trees transport oxygen to roots of rhizomes, reduce sulfide concentrations, and alter microbial communities.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Dissolved oxygen is more readily consumed in the interior of the mangrove forest.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Anthropogenic inputs may push the limits of survival in many mangrove microhabitats.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] For example, shrimp ponds constructed in mangrove forests are considered the greatest anthropogenic threat to mangrove ecosystems.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] These shrimp ponds reduce estuary circulation and water quality which leads to the promotion of diel-cycling hypoxia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] When the quality of the water degrades, the shrimp ponds are quickly abandoned leaving massive amounts of wastewater.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] This is a major source of water pollution that promotes ocean deoxygenation in the adjacent habitats.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Due to these frequent hypoxic conditions, the water does not provide habitats to fish.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] When exposed to extreme hypoxia, ecosystem function can completely collapse.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Extreme deoxygenation will affect the local fish populations, which are an essential food source.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The environmental costs of shrimp farms in the mangrove forests grossly outweigh their economic benefits.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Cessation of shrimp production and restoration of these areas and reduce eutrophication and anthropogenic hypoxia.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In the 1970s, marine dead zones were first noted in settled areas where intensive economic use stimulated scientific scrutiny: in the U.S.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] East Coast's Chesapeake Bay, in Scandinavia's strait called the Kattegat, which is the mouth of the Baltic Sea and in other important Baltic Sea fishing grounds, in the Black Sea, and in the northern Adriatic.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Other marine dead zones have appeared in coastal waters of South America, China, Japan, and New Zealand.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Researchers from Baltic Nest Institute published in one of PNAS issues reports that the dead zones in the Baltic Sea have grown from approximately 5,000 km2 to more than 60,000 km2 in recent years.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Some of the causes behind the elevated increase of dead zones can be attributed to the use of fertilizers, large animal farms, the burning of fossil fuels, and effluents from municipal wastewater treatment plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] With its massive size, the Baltic Sea is best analyzed in sub-areas rather than as a whole.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In a paper published in 2004, researchers specifically divided the Baltic Sea into 9 sub-areas, each having its own specific characteristics.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The 9 sub-areas are discerned as follows: Gulf of Bothnia, Archipelago region, Gulf of Finland, Gulf of Riga, Gulf of Gdansk, Swedish East-coast, Central Baltic, Belt Sea region, and Kattegat.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Each sub-area has responded differently to nutrient additions and eutrophication; however, there are a few general patterns and measures for the Baltic Sea as a whole.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] "Irrespective of the area-specific effects of the increased loads of nutrients to the Baltic Sea, the sources are more or less similar in the whole region.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The extent and the severity of the discharges may differ, however.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] HELCOM (1996) and Rönnberg (2001), the major sources in the input of nutrients are derived from agriculture, industry, municipal sewage and transports.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In general, each area of the Baltic Sea is experiencing similar anthropogenic effects.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] As Rönnberg and Bonsdorff state, "Eutrophication is a serious problem in the Baltic Sea area." However, when it comes to implementation of water revival programs, each area likely will need to be handled on a local level.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] According to the National Geographic, the Chesapeake Bay was one of the first hypoxic zones to be identified in the 1970s.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The Chesapeake Bay experiences seasonal hypoxia due to high nitrogen levels.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] These nitrogen levels are caused by urbanization, there are multiple factories that pollute the atmosphere with nitrogen, and agriculture, the opposite side of the bay is used for poultry farming, which produces a lot of manure that ends up running off into the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] From 1985–2019, there were efforts from the caretakers of Chesapeake Bay to reduce the annual hypoxic volumes.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] There was significant improvement in 2016–2017 that gave assurance to the caretakers that the efforts were successful, however recent data has shown that further efforts are needed to continuously curb the effects of global warming.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The Elizabeth River estuary is used for commercial and military use and is one of the most commonly used ports on the East Coast of the USA.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] From 2015-2019, 11 different conditions were measured in various areas of the Elizabeth River.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Throughout the river, there were consistently high levels of nitrogen and phosphorus, along with high levels of other contaminants contributing to the poor quality of life for bottom feeders along the river.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The main cause of the pollution to the Elizabeth river has been the military and industrial activities through the 1990s.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In 1993, the Elizabeth River Project was started in attempt to do a restoration project on the river.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Adopting one of the fish whose species had been largely impacted by the pollution, the Fundulus heteroclitus (Mummichog), the group was able to gain traction and carry out multiple projects and has removed thousands of tons of contaminated sediment.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In 2006, Maersk-APM, a major shipping company, wanted to build a new port on the Elizabeth River.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] As part of the environmental mitigation they worked with the Elizabeth River Project to create the Money Point Project, which was an effort to restore Money Point, which had been deemed biologically depleted due to a black tar like substance called creosote laying at the bottom.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Maersk-APM gave $5 million to help get the project up and running.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] By 2012, they were able to restore over 7 acres of tidal marsh, 3 acres of oyster reef and created a new shoreline.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] In 2019, the Money Point Project received the "Best Restored Shore" award from the American Shore and Beach Preservation Association.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] A seasonal dead zone exists in the central part of Lake Erie from east of Point Pelee to Long Point and stretches to shores in Canada and the United States.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Between the months of July and October the dead zone has the ability to grow to the size of 10,000 square kilometers.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Lake Erie has an excess of phosphorus due to agricultural runoff that quickens the growth of algae which then contributes to hypoxic conditions.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The superabundance of phosphorus in the lake has been linked to nonpoint source pollution such as urban and agricultural runoff as well as point source pollution that includes sewage and wastewater treatment plants.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] The zone was first noticed in the 1960s amid the peak of eutrophication occurring in the lake.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] After public concern increased, Canada and the US launched efforts to reduce runoff pollution into the lake in the 1970s as means to reverse the dead zone growth.
[src:dead-zone-ecology/dead-zone-ecology] Scientists in 2018 stated that phosphorus runoff would have to further decrease by 40% to avoid the emergence of the dead zones in the area.
